"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757373","Department for Education","false","2017-09-13","<p>There is no definition of a madrassah in education law. An independent institution is required to register as a school provides full-time education to five or more pupils of compulsory school age or one or more pupils with an education, health and care plan (or a statement of special educational need) or who is looked after (within the meaning of section 22 of the Children Act 1989) and is not a school maintained by a local authority or a non-maintained special school. A madrassah will therefore only constitute an unregistered school if it is providing such education.</p><p>LAs have an overarching responsibility of local authorities for safeguarding and promoting the welfare of all children in their area, regardless of where they are educated. It is for local authorities to assess whether the threshold for intervention is met in the case of an individual child taking account of the impact and influence of environmental factors. However, wherever local authorities have reasonable cause to suspect that a child is suffering, or likely to suffer, significant harm, they are under a duty to investigate. Local authorities should make whatever enquiries necessary to decide what, if any, action to take to safeguard or promote the child’s welfare. The police can of course investigate any reports that a crime has been committed in an out-of-school education setting.</p><p>The Government published a Counter Extremism Strategy in 2015, which set out plans to introduce a new system of oversight for out-of-school education settings – such as supplementary schools, tuition centres and madrassahs. To learn more about these settings, and the potential scope and impact of any regulatory system, the department issued a call for evidence. We will make an announcement about the outcome in due course.</p><p>We are supporting local authorities to use their existing powers, as described above, to tackle concerns about the safeguarding of children in unregulated education settings.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash","HL1359","2017-09-13T11:34:01.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757373/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757373/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757373/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-05","Faith Schools: Islam","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they consider that madrassas constitute unregistered schools and are capable of placing children at risk under child protection legislation.","false","Biography information for Lord Warner",,"Lord Warner","HL1358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757374","Department for Education","false","2017-09-13","<p>There is no definition of a madrassah in education law. An independent institution is required to register as a school provides full-time education to five or more pupils of compulsory school age or one or more pupils with an education, health and care plan (or a statement of special educational need) or who is looked after (within the meaning of section 22 of the Children Act 1989) and is not a school maintained by a local authority or a non-maintained special school. A madrassah will therefore only constitute an unregistered school if it is providing such education.</p><p>LAs have an overarching responsibility of local authorities for safeguarding and promoting the welfare of all children in their area, regardless of where they are educated. It is for local authorities to assess whether the threshold for intervention is met in the case of an individual child taking account of the impact and influence of environmental factors. However, wherever local authorities have reasonable cause to suspect that a child is suffering, or likely to suffer, significant harm, they are under a duty to investigate. Local authorities should make whatever enquiries necessary to decide what, if any, action to take to safeguard or promote the child’s welfare. The police can of course investigate any reports that a crime has been committed in an out-of-school education setting.</p><p>The Government published a Counter Extremism Strategy in 2015, which set out plans to introduce a new system of oversight for out-of-school education settings – such as supplementary schools, tuition centres and madrassahs. To learn more about these settings, and the potential scope and impact of any regulatory system, the department issued a call for evidence. We will make an announcement about the outcome in due course.</p><p>We are supporting local authorities to use their existing powers, as described above, to tackle concerns about the safeguarding of children in unregulated education settings.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash","HL1358","2017-09-13T11:34:01.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757374/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757374/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757374/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-05","Faith Schools: Islam","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what progress has been made with the regulation and inspection of madrassas since the announcement made by the then Prime Minister in October 2015; and what powers local authorities and Ofsted have to intervene in the operation of madrassas where there is evidence of child abuse.","false","Biography information for Lord Warner",,"Lord Warner","HL1359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757375","Home Office","false","2017-09-18","<p>Fingerprints taken from visa applicants are normally retained for up to ten years regardless of whether the application was successful, as set out in regulations made under the Nationality, Immigration and Asylum Act 2002.</p><p>This enables the Secretary of State to identify easily those who make further applications for visas to come to the UK, preventing immigration abuse and those who are a risk of high harm from entering the country.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-09-18T13:54:09.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757375/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757375/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757375/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Visas","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether biometric and fingerprint data taken from a visa applicant's application to enter the UK are deleted from any database if that applicant is subsequently refused entry; and if not, for what specific purpose the data are retained.","false","Biography information for Viscount Waverley",,"Viscount Waverley","HL1360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757379","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>Since 1 April 2016, 126 applications have been received and of these 13 are recorded with conditions attached to the approval.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T14:31:12.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757379/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757379/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757379/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-05","Government Property Unit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many times the Government Property Unit has applied conditions to its agreements for Departments to extend or renew their lets in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757380","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>‘Success’ in this context is measured as the percentage of people with a verified identity who are then ‘matched’ with the departmental service they are attempting to access. Matching ensures that the user is shown the correct record within the service. Between January and August 2017, the matching success rate was 88%.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-13T14:22:25.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757380/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757380/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757380/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-05","Electronic Government: Proof of Identity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the success rate is of verified user identities from the Government Verify system being accepted by the departmental service being accessed by that person.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757381","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The GDS academy has trained 2837 public sector workers since 1 September 2016.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T13:43:46.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757381/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757381/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757381/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-05","Civil Servants: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many civil servants have been trained by the Government Digital Service in their digital academy since September 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757382","Cabinet Office","true","2017-09-12","<p><del class="ministerial">The Department does not centrally hold records extending back to the date specified; gathering this data could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</del></p><p><ins class="ministerial">We do not keep records of the number of GDS staff who have ever been on the civil service fast stream; however, there are currently 16 fast streamers working at GDS.</ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial"><strong></strong></ins><br /><br /></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T10:32:25.573Z","2017-09-13T08:46:48.757Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757382/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757382/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757382/answer","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757382/answer/previousversion/10242","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-05","Government Digital Service: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many members of staff of the Government Digital Service have come from the civil service fast stream.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757383","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>To date, 1.5m people have used GOV.UK Verify to perform 3.7m secure transactions. HMG has committed to rollout Verify across departmental services. To facilitate this, we continue to innovate and improve the GOV.UK Verify service in order to support departments’ transformation plans and the migration of citizen-facing services from Government Gateway.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>In addition to continuing with the rollout of GOV.UK Verify across central government, we also continue to explore the wider applications for <a href="http://gov.uk" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a> Verify for secure citizen identity verification in both the wider public and private sectors.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>We remain confident that this planned activity enables us to work towards 25m users by 2020.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-13T14:26:12.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757383/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757383/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757383/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-05","Electronic Government: Proof of Identity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Government is on track to meet the target of 25 million people using the Verify service by April 2020.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757384","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-13","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>There are currently 14 departmental services accessible through GOV.UK Verify. They are:</p><ul><li><p>Vehicle Operator Licensing (DVLA)</p></li><li><p>Digital mortgaging service (HM Land Registry)</p></li><li><p>Personal Tax Account (HMRC)</p></li><li><p>Check your income tax (HMRC)</p></li><li><p>Report a medical condition that affects your driving (DVLA)</p></li><li><p>Renew your short term medical driving licence (DVLA)</p></li><li><p>Check your State Pension (DWP)</p></li><li><p>Universal Credit Digital Service (DWP)</p></li><li><p>View or share your driving licence information (DVLA)</p></li><li><p>Claim for redundancy payment (Insolvency Service)</p></li><li><p>Help your friends or family with their tax (HMRC)</p></li><li><p>Self Assessment (HMRC)</p></li><li><p>Rural Payments (DEFRA)</p></li><li><p>PAYE for employees: company car tax (HMRC)</p></li></ul><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The following services have also connected to GOV.UK Verify, but are not currently available to the public:</p><ul><li><p>Tax credits service (HMRC)</p></li><li><p>Claim a tax refund (HMRC)</p></li><li><p>Marriage Allowance (HMRC)</p></li></ul><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-13T14:18:08.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757384/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757384/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757384/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-05","Electronic Government: Proof of Identity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which departmental services have connected to the Government Verify service.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757385","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>Total savings from digital and technology spend controls, which are operated by Government Digital Service on behalf of HM Treasury, are set out below. These have been audited by GIAA on behalf of NAO.</p><ul><li><p>2012/13: £365m*</p></li><li><p>2013/14: £91m</p></li><li><p>2014/15: £391m</p></li><li><p>2015/16: £339m</p></li></ul><p><strong> </strong></p><p>* this figure also includes transformation savings</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T13:04:05.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757385/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757385/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757385/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-05","Government Digital Service: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the value is of savings from the Governmental Digital Service's spending controls in each year since 2011.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757386","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Cabinet Office continues to keep all its spending controls under review to ensure they remain fit for purpose.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T13:07:09.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757386/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757386/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757386/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-05","Government Digital Service: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether he plans to make any changes to the spending controls issued by the Government Digital Service.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8516"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757387","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>Government takes email security seriously but has no plans to publish details of specific monitoring or vulnerabilities. The National Cyber Security Centre, together with Government Digital Service, advocates the use of the DMARC protocol that makes email spoofing much harder.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>In parallel, the National Cyber Security Centre has built a Mail Check service that monitors adoption of these standards. In May 2017 1,070 domains were using the Mail Check service, rising to 1,208 in June and 1,224 in July.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-13T15:08:35.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757387/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757387/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757387/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-05","Government Departments: Email","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Government Digital Service will publish the findings of its central monitoring of email vulnerability levels for departments since April 2017.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8517"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757388","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The updated List of Ministerial Responsibilities will be published shortly on GOV.UK. Copies will be available in the Vote Office of the House of Commons, and also on request.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-09-12T09:07:22.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757388/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757388/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757388/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-05","Government Departments: Ministerial Responsibility","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, when he expects to provide an updated list of ministerial responsibilities, including for executive agencies and non-ministerial departments; and if copies will be made available in the Vote Office of the House of Commons.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","8525"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757389","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>I refer the Honourable Member to my previous answer [7702].</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-09-13T16:09:59.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757389/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757389/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757389/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-05","Business Appointments Advisory Committee: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many letters have been published on the ACOBA website more than one month after the letter being sent in (a) the last 12 months and (b) each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757390","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Government is committed to tackling the causes of problem debt, and is aware of the Citizens Advice report, although it is not the practice to respond directly to such reports.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has fundamentally reformed regulation of the consumer credit market, transferring regulatory responsibility from the Office of Fair Trading (OFT) to the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) on 1 April 2014. This more robust regulatory system is delivering the Government’s vision for a well-functioning and sustainable consumer credit market which is able to meet consumers’ needs.</p><p> </p><p>Since the transfer, the FCA has taken a proactive approach on consumer credit, including overdrafts, to ensure that all consumers who use high-cost credit products are treated fairly. As a result of its Credit Card Market Study, the FCA has also taken action to tackle persistent debt in the credit card market. As part of this, the industry has also developed a voluntary agreement to give greater control to customers and to restrict offers of credit limit increases.</p><p> </p><p>The Government also believes that consumers need free at the point of use help with their finances. In the Queen’s Speech, the Government announced the Financial Guidance and Claims Bill. This will legislate to restructure the financial guidance landscape and bring debt advice, money guidance, and pensions guidance together in a single body, and give consumers better access to the financial information they need. This Bill is currently going through Parliament.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-13T15:00:44.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757390/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757390/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757390/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-05","Debts","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if his Department will respond to the recommendations of the Citizens Advice Bureau report, Stuck in Debt, on forcing lenders to scrap unarranged overdraft fees, prohibiting lenders from increasing a credit limit without a customer's permission, offering financial advice and making debt plans legally enforceable.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","8519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757391","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government has no current plans to introduce a Class 3 National Insurance credit for volunteers.</p><p> </p><p>However on 6 September, a Call For Evidence was published on the Full-Time Social Action Review which will develop recommendations on how to support full time volunteering.</p><p> </p><p>Details of how to submit evidence are available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/643612/Full_Time_Social_Action_Review_-_Call_for_Evidence.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/643612/Full_Time_Social_Action_Review_-_Call_for_Evidence.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>The review will consider what the voluntary sector, industry and, if needed, government can do to support full-time volunteering.</p><p> </p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman","8437 ; 8438","2017-09-12T16:02:57.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757391/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757391/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757391/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-05","National Insurance Contributions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans he has to introduce provisions relating to Class 3 national insurance credits in the National Insurance Contributions Bill.","false","Biography information for Michael Tomlinson","Mid Dorset and North Poole","Michael Tomlinson","8487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757392","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-13","<p>The government established an independent <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Financial_Policy_Committee" target="_blank">Financial Policy Committee</a> (FPC), giving the FPC a primary objective to identify, monitor and take action to remove or reduce systemic risks with a view to protecting and enhancing financial stability. The FPC’s June 2017 Financial Stability Report (FSR), published on 27 June, assesses recent trends in unsecured debt in the consumer credit market. The FSR notes that consumer credit has been growing rapidly, but that loss rates on consumer credit lending are low at present. The June FSR announced that the FPC will: bring forward its assessment of stressed losses on consumer credit lending in the Bank’s 2017 annual stress test; and support the Prudential Regulation Authority and Financial Conduct Authority in their intention to publish their expectations of lenders in the consumer credit market.</p><p> </p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-13T15:09:27.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757392/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757392/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757392/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-05","Debts","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps his Department is taking to reduce levels of unsecured debt.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","8523"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757393","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Royal College of Nursing (RCN) reported that 700 nurses and health care assistants applied for hardship grants from the RCN in 2016 and 25% of grants were to staff who were full time employees. These are very small numbers compared with the 435,000 membership the RCN reports.</p><p> </p><p>Nursing remains an attractive career with access to a package of employment benefits that are significantly more generous than those typically available in the private sector. This includes an excellent pension and competitive maternity, sickness and leave entitlement.</p><p> </p><p>For the mean annual earnings per nurse, the latest figures of April 2016 to March 2017‎ taken from the NHS staff earnings survey carried out by NHS Digital were £31,341<sup>1</sup>.</p><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><p><sup>1</sup> <a href="https://digital.nhs.uk/catalogue/PUB30002" target="_blank">https://digital.nhs.uk/catalogue/PUB30002</a></p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-09-11T15:11:53.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757393/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757393/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757393/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Health Professions: Grants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the statement from the Royal College of Nursing of 4 March 2017 on the number of nurses and healthcare assistants who applied for hardship grants in 2016; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","8589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757394","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-13","<p>I set out the Government’s current position on public sector pay in the House of Commons on 12 September 2017. A copy of those exchanges is available at: <strong><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2017-09-12/HCWS127" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2017-09-12/HCWS127</a> </strong></p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-13T15:58:03.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757394/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757394/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757394/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-05","Public Sector: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make it his policy to end public sector pay restraint in the Autumn Budget 2017.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","8567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757395","Department for Education","false","2017-09-12","<p>Since 2010, we have taken significant steps to equalise the state benefits provided to the employed and self-employed, including giving the self-employed access to the full rate of the new State Pension for the first time, (worth up to £1,800/year more).</p><p> </p><p>We continue to keep all differences in treatment between self-employed and employed people under review.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-09-12T16:36:29.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757395/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757395/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757395/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-05","Self-employed: Adoption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the Answer of 29 March 2017 to Question 69018, for what reasons the Government consultation on the case for introducing an adoption allowance similar to maternity allowance for self-employed adopters is no longer being brought forward; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","8590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757396","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Barnett Formula determines changes to each devolved administration’s funding with reference to changes in DEL funding for UK government departments. There was no change in DEL funding for UK government departments as a result of the financial support announced for Northern Ireland in June 2017.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-12T12:59:13.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757396/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757396/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757396/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-05","Public Expenditure: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of increasing Barnett formula funding for Wales in line with the recent increase in funding for Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","8645"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757397","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Government has undertaken a significant amount of work to assess the economic and fiscal impacts of leaving the EU. This is part of our continuing programme of rigorous and extensive analytical work covering a range of scenarios on a sector by sector basis.</p><p> </p><p>We are seeking the best possible deal for the United Kingdom and the work being done reflects this.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-13T15:11:25.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757397/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757397/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757397/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-05","Economic Situation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the number of jobs at risk of being lost in the UK economy as a result of no deal being reached on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","8581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757398","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-13","<p>The readability of the terms and conditions set out in life insurance policies falls within the remit of the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA). As such, HM Treasury has not conducted research into this topic.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA is the UK’s conduct of business regulator and is an independent public body. The FCA has confirmed that it will provide a written response to the Member’s question. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","9036","2017-09-13T15:13:49.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757398/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757398/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757398/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-05","Life Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what research his Department has conducted into the readability of the terms and conditions set out in life insurance policies.","false","Biography information for Thelma Walker","Colne Valley","Thelma Walker","8661"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757399","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-12","<p>Compliance monitoring and enforcement of the Construction Products Regulation is carried out by local authorities’ Weights and Measures (Trading Standards) in England, Scotland and Wales and District Councils in Northern Ireland, not the Department for Communities and Local Government.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-12T13:07:03.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757399/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757399/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757399/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-05","Construction Products Regulations 2013","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what penalties his Department has imposed on businesses not complying with the Construction Products Regulations 2013 since those regulations were introduced.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","8584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757400","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-12","<p>As announced by the Prime Minister on 15 August, it is incredibly important that we look into the wider questions raised by the Grenfell Tower fire – including around social housing – and how best to address these issues.</p><p>In taking this forward, it is also important that we engage directly with social tenants to help build up a comprehensive picture of some of the immediate issues they are facing, as well as to identify any common concerns that must inform any national approach.</p><p>I have met with representatives of national tenant organisations to seek their views on this process, and a programme of events is currently been drawn up for me to personally meet and hear from as many social tenants both in the immediate area around Grenfell Tower, but also across the country. There will be further announcements on this work shortly as arrangements are finalised.</p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-12T15:52:49.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757400/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757400/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757400/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757400/answer/previousversion/9853","Biography information for Alok Sharma","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-05","Grenfell Tower Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what progress has been made on identifying and addressing issues in social housing referred to in the Prime Minister's statement on the Grenfell Tower inquiry terms of reference of 15 August 2017; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","8585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757401","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Department is working closely with those responsible for co-ordinating the Grenfell Tower Mental Health response.</p><p> </p><p>The National Health Service has had staff on the ground since day one, helping the people affected first with the immediate physical health emergency, and, as time has moved on, with developing psychological health and wellbeing needs. This was phase 1 of our response plan. We are now in phase 2.</p><p> </p><p>Phase 1 comprised treating the physical symptoms, making sure patients are general practitioner (GP) registered and know where to go, putting resilient systems in place for when the psychological impact kicks in, planning ahead and ensuring adequate primary care and mental health resource is in place, and ensuring all NHS organisations are united and efficiently coordinated.</p><p> </p><p>Phase 2 comprises implementing a ‘screen and treat’ programme to proactively contact people affected by the fire, beginning with those who also have a long-term health condition, and assess the psychological impact the fire has had on them. The first 1,200 screenings have begun. If a patient shows signs of trauma such as Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder symptoms they will be referred on to a mental health professional or appropriate wellbeing service. If they are not showing signs of trauma at this time, the GP will follow up with them again in a suitable period of time.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-09-11T14:31:09.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757401/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757401/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757401/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Grenfell Tower: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of provision of mental health support, trauma counselling and bereavement counselling for the survivors of Grenfell Tower and their families; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","8586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757402","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Department published guidance on 20 April 2017. This can be viewed via the following link:</p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/adoption-of-roads-by-highway-authorities" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/adoption-of-roads-by-highway-authorities</a></p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-12T08:53:15.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757402/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757402/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757402/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-05","Local Government: Private Roads","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what guidance his Department has published on local authorities adopting new private roads.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","8548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757403","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-13","<p>These units are covered by a harmonized European product standard (EN 1279-5) and so the Construction Products Regulation (EU 305/2011) applies to their manufacture, import and distribution. This regulation sets requirements for placing construction products onto the market, not their installation.</p><p>Monitoring compliance and enforcement duties fall to trading standards bodies in England, Scotland and Wales and District Councils in Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-13T16:57:40.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757403/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757403/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757403/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-05","Housing: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department takes to ensure that the sale and installation of narrow-cavity, low-sightline glass-sealed units into heritage windows is compliant with the Construction Products Regulations 2013.","false","Biography information for Ronnie Cowan","Inverclyde","Ronnie Cowan","8493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757404","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-14","<p>I refer my Hon Friend to the answer given on 11 September to Question UIN 8612.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-09-14T14:32:07.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757404/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757404/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757404/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-05","Railways: Tickets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what progress he has made on introducing flexible ticketing for part-time commuters.","false","Biography information for James Cartlidge","South Suffolk","James Cartlidge","8494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757405","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-12","<p>EU Construction Products Regulations (EU 305/2011) are enforced under the UK Construction Products Regulations 2013 (SI 2013/1387).</p><p>Compliance monitoring and enforcement duties fall to local authorities’ Weights and Measures (Trading Standards) in England, Scotland and Wales and District Councils in Northern Ireland. It is for these bodies to determine how they carry out their duties but they follow the Enforcement Concordat (<a href="http://www.berr.gov.uk/files/file10150.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.berr.gov.uk/files/file10150.pdf</a>) and the Regulators Compliance Code (<a href="http://www.berr.gov.uk/files/file45019.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.berr.gov.uk/files/file45019.pdf</a>).</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-12T13:57:05.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757405/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757405/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757405/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-05","Construction Products Regulations 2013","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department takes to ensure that trading standards departments enforce the Construction Products Regulations 2013.","false","Biography information for Ronnie Cowan","Inverclyde","Ronnie Cowan","8495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757406","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-13","<p>The government is committed to eliminating the gender pay gap. As a public service broadcaster funded by the licence fee, the BBC has a responsibility to set an example for others and lead the way in promoting equality in the workplace. It is for the BBC to determine how to close its gender pay gap and we expect to see improvement in next year's disclosure.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-09-13T14:55:12.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757406/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757406/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757406/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-05","BBC: Equal Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps her Department is taking to help reduce the gender pay gap at the BBC.","false","Biography information for Thelma Walker","Colne Valley","Thelma Walker","8662"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757407","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-13","<p>An announcement will be made in October.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-09-13T14:36:01.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757407/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757407/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757407/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-05","Gaming Machines: Reviews","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to the Answer of 12 September 2016 to Question 45539 from the right hon. Member for East Ham, on gaming machines, when the Triennial Review of Stakes and Prizes will be published.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","8643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757408","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-13","<p>On 24 August the Gambling Commission published a report that draws together evidence on gambling behaviour, including that on fixed odds betting terminals, in England, Scotland and Wales.</p><p> </p><p>The report can be found here:<br></p><p>http://www.gamblingcommission.gov.uk/PDF/survey-data/Gambling-behaviour-in-Great-Britain-2015.pdf</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","8554","2017-09-13T14:39:43.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757408/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757408/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757408/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-05","Gaming Machines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate her Department has made of the proportion of funds staked on fixed-odds betting terminals that is staked by (a) problem gamblers and (b) people who are in receipt of benefits.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","8553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757409","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-13","<p>On 24 August the Gambling Commission published a report that draws together evidence on gambling behaviour, including that on fixed odds betting terminals, in England, Scotland and Wales.</p><p> </p><p>The report can be found here:<br></p><p>http://www.gamblingcommission.gov.uk/PDF/survey-data/Gambling-behaviour-in-Great-Britain-2015.pdf</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","8553","2017-09-13T14:39:43.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757409/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757409/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757409/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-05","Gaming Machines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate her Department has made of the total number of people in receipt of benefits who regularly use fixed-odds betting terminals.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","8554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757410","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-09-13","<p>A future partnership between the UK and EU is in the interests of both sides, and we have entered into the negotiations anticipating success. However, since the result of the referendum, we have taken the responsible approach to work at pace to build a detailed understanding of how withdrawing from the EU will affect policies and services for a range of outcomes, including the unlikely scenario in which no mutually satisfactory agreement can be reached. Given the long lead-in times to implement some of our contingency measures, we can't wait until we see the final outcome of the negotiations to begin our preparations. But implementing the first stages of contingency plans now should not be interpreted as an expectation that talks with the EU will not be successful, but recognised instead as the actions of a responsible government determined to ensure a smooth exit under any eventuality.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-09-13T16:28:45.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757410/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757410/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757410/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-09-05","Ministry of Defence: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what contingency planning has been conducted by his Department in the event that no deal is reached on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","8580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757411","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-09-07","<p>The UK has neither a first use nor a no first use policy for our nuclear weapons.</p><p>It is essential that we do not assist our potential adversaries by defining precisely when, how and at what scale we would contemplate employing them in the most extreme circumstances of self-defence, including the defence of our NATO allies.</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon",,"2017-09-07T15:28:51.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757411/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757411/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757411/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-09-05","Nuclear Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will adopt a no first use policy in relation to the UK's nuclear weapons capability; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","8502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757412","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-09-12","<p>All exports of controlled military equipment and dual-use equipment are assessed against the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria. Similarly, Government proposals to gift controlled military equipment and dual-use equipment are also assessed against the Consolidated Criteria, with the same degree of rigour.</p><p>The Consolidated Criteria provide a thorough risk assessment framework, which requires us to think hard about the impact of providing equipment. Under Criterion 7, we would not grant an export licence, or gift equipment, if there was an unacceptable risk that the items would be diverted within the destination country or re-exported under undesirable conditions.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-09-12T16:46:30.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757412/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757412/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757412/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-09-05","Iraq: Arms Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps his Department takes to ensure that weapons sold to or gifted to Iraq reach their designated destination and end user.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","8470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757413","Department for Education","false","2017-09-13","<p>Schools play a vital role in promoting integration and promoting an understanding of different faiths and communities. We will continue to work closely with Church and faith schools to promote and support integration and will set out further details of our approach in this area and in relation to the 50% cap on faith admissions in faith free schools in due course.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-09-13T15:38:58.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757413/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757413/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757413/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-05","Faith Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on the removal of the cap on faith admissions; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Pound","Ealing North","Stephen Pound","8497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757414","Department for Education","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Government want schools to have the resources they need to deliver a high quality education for their pupils. This is why we have announced that under the National Funding Formula there will be an additional £1.3 billion for schools and high needs across 2018-19 and 2019-20. This means that core funding for schools and high needs will rise from almost £41 billion in 2017-18 to £42.4 billion in 2018-19. In 2019-20, this will rise again to £43.5 billion.</p><p> </p><p>An in-year deficit is not an issue in itself unless it is symptomatic of a trend towards a cumulative deficit. Schools may draw on their reserves in a particular year – for example to spend on capital projects.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not collect data on balance projections, including in-year deficits, for maintained schools. Academy trusts are obliged to provide the Education and Skills Funding Agency (ESFA) with an unaudited Budget Forecast Return (BFR) each year, to allow us to view their current and expected end of year position. Since the BFR is only an unaudited forecast, we do not use it as a basis for estimates. An audited financial statement is published by trusts at the end of the financial year, confirming their actual financial position for that year.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-09-13T16:11:39.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757414/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757414/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757414/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-05","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the number of schools in (a) England and (b) each local authority in England projecting that they will run an in-year deficit in the next three years.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","8530"
