"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757425","Department for Education","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Government is committed to widening participation to higher education for students from disadvantaged and under-represented groups. Figures from UCAS figures show that the entry rate for disadvantaged young people to the most selective institutions –such as those from the Russell Group - has increased 52% proportionally between 2009 and 2016.</p><p>The latest guidance from Government to the Director of Fair Access (February 2016) acknowledges that, whilst selective institutions have made progress in widening access to higher education, more could and should be done. As such we have asked the Director to challenge institutions to see that more progress is made. Through the access agreement process there are regular discussions with each higher education institution about their plans and progress in widening participation.</p><p> </p><p>In its strategic plan the Office for Fair Access has set the sector an objective, to be achieved by 2019-20, to make faster progress to increase the entry rate of students from under-represented and disadvantaged groups entering more selective institutions and narrow the participation gap between people from the most and least advantaged backgrounds at such institutions.</p><p> </p><p>From January 2018, the Office for Students (OfS), with a new Director for Fair Access and Participation appointed by the Secretary of State, will take on responsibility for widening participation in higher education. The OfS will have a statutory duty to promote equality of opportunity across the whole lifecycle for disadvantaged students, not just access. As a result, widening access and participation will be at the core of the OfS’ functions. In addition, our reforms will introduce a Transparency Duty requiring higher education providers to publish application, offer, acceptance, dropout and attainment rates of students broken down by ethnicity, gender and socio-economic background.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","8556 ; 8562","2017-09-13T16:24:36.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757425/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757425/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757425/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-05","Universities: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what guidance her Department provides to Russell Group universities on improving access for students from disadvantaged and under-represented backgrounds.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","8558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757426","Department for Education","false","2017-09-13","<p>The latest available information is published as part of the underlying data for the Statistical First Release, School Workforce in England 2016. This is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/school-workforce-in-england-november-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/school-workforce-in-england-november-2016</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The published data shows that in 2016, Haringey had a vacancy rate of 0.3%. For Inner London, the vacancy rate was 0.2%.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-09-13T16:06:06.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757426/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757426/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757426/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-05","Teachers: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the level of teacher shortages in (a) the London Borough of Haringey and (b) London.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","8559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757427","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-12","<p>Leaving the EU presents a major opportunity for UK agriculture. We are working towards achieving the best possible deal for the UK agriculture industry, and we want to secure a deep and comprehensive Free-Trade Agreement as an alternative to membership of the Single Market.</p><p>We are conducting rigorous analysis of various trade scenarios on UK agriculture as part of our planning. Other organisations have also conducted external analysis of future trading scenarios and their potential impact on the sector.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","6872","2017-09-12T13:04:12.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757427/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757427/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757427/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-05","Agriculture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of the effect on the UK farming industry in the event that no deal is reached on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","8578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757428","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Government continues to take a responsible approach in preparing plans for all exit scenarios. Over the past year, every government department has been working at pace to build a detailed understanding of how withdrawing from the EU will affect its existing policies and services across a wide range of outcomes. Planning for all scenarios is in no way representative of how talks are proceeding or indicative of our preferred outcome.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-13T13:24:46.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757428/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757428/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757428/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-05","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what contingency planning his Department has carried out for the possibility that there is no deal reached on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","8577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757429","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-13","<p>This information is not held by the Government.</p><p>According to an industry report, (Public &amp; Corporate Economic Consultants report 2014: The Value of Shooting, found at www.shootingfacts.co.uk) shooting as a whole is estimated to be worth about £2 billion a year to the economy, supporting more than 70,000 full-time equivalent jobs.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-09-13T09:00:19.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757429/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757429/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757429/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-05","Gun Sports: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many people have been employed in shooting sports in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","8482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757430","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-13","<p>Nature conservation is a devolved matter. In England all wild birds are protected under the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981, making it an offence to kill, injure or take wild birds or to take or damage their eggs and nests. There are provisions under Section 16 of the 1981 Act that allow for the control of raptors for specific reasons, for example, to conserve other wild birds. Licence applications are dealt with on a case by case basis and priority must be given to non-lethal methods. The Government is not considering any further controls on the number of raptors.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-09-13T09:02:20.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757430/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757430/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757430/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-05","Birds of Prey","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will consider controls on the number of raptor birds in the countryside.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","8483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757431","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-13","<p>This is a devolved matter so this reply relates to England only.</p><p>The table below shows licences issued in England under Section 16(1)(k) of the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981, to allow the killing of ravens for the purposes of prevention of damage to livestock (in all cases sheep).</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>2017/18 (to date)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Licences issued</strong></p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-09-13T09:05:55.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757431/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757431/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757431/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-05","Ravens: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many licences have been issued to control ravens in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","8479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757432","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-13","<p>This information is not held by the Government.</p><p>According to an industry report, (Public &amp; Corporate Economic Consultants report 2014: The Value of Shooting, found at www.shootingfacts.co.uk) shooting as a whole is estimated to be worth about £2 billion a year to the economy, supporting more than 70,000 full-time equivalent jobs.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-09-13T09:01:16.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757432/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757432/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757432/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-05","Gun Sports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate he has made of the value of shooting sports to the UK in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","8480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757433","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The UK Government regularly raises a range of issues with Qatar. The most recent discussion about the Muslim Brotherhood was by senior officials on 7 June.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-12T09:25:21.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757433/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757433/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757433/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","Qatar: Muslim Brotherhood","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his counterpart in Qatar on the funding of the Muslim Brotherhood.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","8471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757434","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>​During my most recent visit to Turkey on 16-17 August, I emphasised the need for Turkey to respect human rights, including press freedom and the rule of law. Our officials in Turkey monitor the human rights situation closely and human rights remains a priority for our support to civil society projects there.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-09-13T15:09:07.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757434/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757434/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757434/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","Turkey: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his Turkish counterpart on human rights abuses in that country.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","8472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757435","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The UK Government firmly believes corruption is at the heart of many of the world’s problems and we support Egyptian Government efforts to counter corruption. The UK is actively engaged with the World Bank’s Country Partnership Framework for Egypt, whose interventions will assist in reducing corruption in the country.</p><p>The UK continues to hold a number of assets belonging to persons identified as responsible for misappropriation of Egyptian state funds under the 2011 EU sanctions regime, and we will continue to support anti-corruption efforts in Egypt.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-12T09:38:15.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757435/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757435/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757435/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","Egypt: Corruption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his Egyptian counterpart on allegations of corruption in that country.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","8473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757436","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to the statement made by my Rt Hon Friend, the Foreign Secretary on 5 September (<a href="https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2017-09-05/debates/C42A1D96-73C1-4D71-883E-BC8F83842285/KoreanPeninsula" target="_blank">https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2017-09-05/debates/C42A1D96-73C1-4D71-883E-BC8F83842285/KoreanPeninsula</a>). The Foreign Secretary regulary speaks to US Secretary of State Tillerson about the situation in North Korea. We are working with the US and our partners in the region to bring this crisis to a diplomatic end.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-09-13T15:04:09.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757436/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757436/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757436/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","North Korea: Guided Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his US counterpart on recent missile tests in North Korea; whether he has made any (a) political and (b) military commitments to the US relating to North Korea; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","8499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757437","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to the statement made by my Rt Hon Friend the Foreign Secretary (<a href="https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2017-09-05/debates/C42A1D96-73C1-4D71-883E-BC8F83842285/KoreanPeninsula" target="_blank">https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2017-09-05/debates/C42A1D96-73C1-4D71-883E-BC8F83842285/KoreanPeninsula</a>). North Korea has to provide a credible and genuine signal it is ready to discuss denuclearisation. The UK has been clear that we support dialogue under the right circumstances. We are working closely with partners to bring home to North Korea that a change in direction will open the way towards a peaceful resolution and a secure future.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-09-13T15:51:39.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757437/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757437/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757437/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","North Korea: International Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the Government is taking steps to promote (a) bilateral dialogue between North Korea and the US and (b) six party dialogue with North Korea; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","8501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757438","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Secretary of State for Defence is responsible for the Sovereign Base Areas (SBAs) of Akrotiri and Dhekelia. The SBA Administration holds and exchanges information with relevant authorities in the Republic of Cyprus and Non-Government Organisations on illegal bird trapping activity in the SBAs; this includes detailed analysis and maps of those sites forming part of Special Areas of Conservation and numbers of arrests and seizures of bird trapping equipment that take place in the SBAs.</p><p>The SBAs in Cyprus are covered by the Bern convention on the conservation of European wildlife and natural habitats and adhere to its provisions. The Bern Convention and SBA Legislation require the SBA Administration to report on the effectiveness of conservation measures taken to maintain the favourable conservation status of designated habitats. This includes information and records on removal of bird trapping paraphernalia.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-09-13T16:29:13.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757438/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757438/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757438/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-09-05","Cyprus: Military Bases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what information his Department holds on illegal killing of wild birds on the sovereign bases on Akrotiri and Dhekelia.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","8526"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757439","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>Our Ambassador in Tehran raises the cases of our British/Iranian dual national detainees, including Mr Kamal Foroughi, at every opportunity as part of his regular discussions with the Iranian Government. This happened most recently on 30 August. I also raised the cases of our dual national detainees with the Iranian Foreign Minister and Deputy Foreign Minister when I visited Tehran on 5 August. While Iran does not recognise dual nationality and regards them as Iranian, we consider them British and will continue to raise these cases and request consular access.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-12T09:45:32.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757439/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757439/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757439/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","Kamal Foroughi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, on how many occasions the UK Ambassador to Iran has had discussions with the Iranian Government on Kamal Foroughi since his appointment; and what recent progress has been made on securing his release.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","8576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757440","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office and our Embassy in Bahrain continue to closely monitor Mohammed Ramadan and Hussein Ali Mousa's cases. The UK is firmly opposed to the death penalty, and our longstanding policy is to oppose capital sentences in all circumstances. We continue to raise concerns about these cases in public and in private at the most senior levels. We understand the Ombudsman and the Special Investigations Unit continue with their investigations. We do not know when these will be concluded or published but continue to encourage a swift, transparent conclusion.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-11T17:00:36.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757440/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757440/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757440/answer","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757440/answer/previousversion/9980","Biography information for Alistair Burt","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","Bahrain: Capital Punishment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to the Answer of 21 March 2017 to Question HL5901, on Bahrain: capital punishment, when his Department expects the findings of the Ombudsman and Special Investigations Unit investigation into the allegations of torture of Mohammed Ramadan and Hussein Ali Mousa to be published.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","8591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757441","Department of Health","false","2017-09-13","<p>In June 2017, the Queen’s Speech confirmed that the Government would publish a Bill in draft that will legislate for a new independent health service safety investigations body. We intend to publish the Bill in draft shortly and anticipate this would be followed by a process of pre-legislative scrutiny.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-09-13T10:49:49.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757441/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757441/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757441/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Health Services: Public Bodies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he plans to bring forward legislative proposals to create an independent healthcare safety investigations body in the NHS.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","8572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757442","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Government has both non-legislative and legislative barriers to integration under review including those related to workforce, information sharing and funding. We are continuously building the evidence-base, sharing best practice and using feedback from local areas to inform changes that will reduce barriers and further join up care.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-11T14:22:03.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757442/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757442/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757442/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Health Services: Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans he has to make non-legislative changes to remove barriers to the integration of care; and if he will make statement.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","8573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757443","Department of Health","false","2017-09-13","<p>NHS England have published, at a national level, documents which describe the overall approach.</p><p>Individual clinical commissioning groups directly affected will reflect the impact of the capped expenditure process as part of their publication of plans, and will comply with any further requirements for consultation.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-09-13T10:39:01.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757443/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757443/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757443/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","NHS: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will publish all documentation relating to the capped expenditure process.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","8574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757444","Department of Health","false","2017-09-13","<p>This information is not collected centrally.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","8564","2017-09-13T16:23:00.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757444/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757444/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757444/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Essure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will estimate the cost to the NHS of follow-up surgery for patients who have been given an Essure implant.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","8568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757445","Department of Health","false","2017-09-13","<p>Following the suspension of the CE certificate for Essure devices, the manufacturer has agreed to voluntarily quarantine Essure stock in the United Kingdom. Patient safety is our highest priority and we encourage the reporting of any adverse incidents to the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency (MHRA), regardless of how long ago the implant was inserted. The MHRA are bound by UK and European Union legislation that preclude us from releasing the information that has been requested. However, there is currently no evidence to suggest any increased risk to patient safety. Any women with questions should speak to their general practitioner or healthcare professional.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-13T16:28:54.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757445/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757445/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757445/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Essure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many women have reported problems to the Medicines and Healthcare Products Regulatory Agency about the Essure implant in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","8569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757446","Department of Health","false","2017-09-13","<p>£100 million of capital funding has been made available for primary care streaming in accident and emergency departments. This was confirmed in the budget statement of 8 March 2017. Since then 117 sites across 102 trusts have been successful in bidding for this funding, with a total of £90,857,030 million allocated. Each of these trusts has confirmed that this will add or increase capacity for clinical streaming, or improve patient flow through the emergency department. NHS England and NHS Improvement remain committed to have primary care streaming, or an equivalent local model, in all emergency departments by October 2017 and will monitor both the implementation and impact of streaming thereafter.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-09-13T10:18:18.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757446/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757446/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757446/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Accident and Emergency Departments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 29 June 2017 to Question 822, on accident and emergency departments, what progress is being made on introducing front-door clinical streaming in accident and emergency departments by October 2017.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","8570"
