"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757622","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-12","<p>Assessments of the effectiveness of all badger culls undertaken from 2013 to 2016 have been published and can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/bovine-tb-controlling-the-risk-of-bovine-tb-from-badgers" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/bovine-tb-controlling-the-risk-of-bovine-tb-from-badgers</a>.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-12T12:24:17.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757622/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757622/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757622/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-05","Bovine Tuberculosis: Disease Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether he plans to publish an assessment of the effectiveness of the trial of badger culls in Gloucestershire and Somerset as part of the Government's bovine TB strategy.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","8967"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757623","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-12","<p>Badgers removed under licence during the pilot culls in Gloucestershire and Somerset were not routinely tested for TB. The RBCT and previous Road Traffic Accident surveys found TB in around one third of all badgers in these areas.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-12T12:22:45.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757623/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757623/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757623/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-05","Bovine Tuberculosis: Disease Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many and what proportion of badgers culled in the trials in Gloucestershire and Somerset were infected with bovine TB.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","8966"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757624","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Environment Agency revoked the operator’s permit in April 2016 and served notice against the operator to clear the site by 16 September 2016. When the operator failed to clear the site the Environment Agency started a formal investigation to take firm enforcement action against the operator.</p><p> </p><p>Investigations at this level can take some time to complete as the Environment Agency wants to build the best and strongest case against an offender, particularly if an investigation is complex as for the site operated by Rowan Oak Waste at Shaw Road in Dudley. During the investigation the Environment Agency has also been working hard to get the landowner to take responsibility for clearing the waste. By 5 September 2017, 290 tonnes of waste have been removed with the Environment Agency making sure that all waste leaving the site is disposed of legitimately.</p><p> </p><p>The case is currently being reviewed by the Environment Agency legal team and once this review has been completed the Environment Agency will be taking the next step towards appropriate enforcement action against the operator.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","7399 ; 8929","2017-09-11T16:59:04.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757624/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757624/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757624/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-05","Rowanoak Waste Services: Dudley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answers of 25 July 2017 to Questions 5342, 5394, 5395 and 5396, if he will make an assessment of the effectiveness of the Environment Agency in dealing with the site operated by Rowan Oak Waste at Shaw Road in Dudley; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","8928"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757625","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Environment Agency revoked the operator’s permit in April 2016 and served notice against the operator to clear the site by 16 September 2016. When the operator failed to clear the site the Environment Agency started a formal investigation to take firm enforcement action against the operator.</p><p> </p><p>Investigations at this level can take some time to complete as the Environment Agency wants to build the best and strongest case against an offender, particularly if an investigation is complex as for the site operated by Rowan Oak Waste at Shaw Road in Dudley. During the investigation the Environment Agency has also been working hard to get the landowner to take responsibility for clearing the waste. By 5 September 2017, 290 tonnes of waste have been removed with the Environment Agency making sure that all waste leaving the site is disposed of legitimately.</p><p> </p><p>The case is currently being reviewed by the Environment Agency legal team and once this review has been completed the Environment Agency will be taking the next step towards appropriate enforcement action against the operator.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","7399 ; 8928","2017-09-11T16:59:05.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757625/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757625/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757625/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-05","Rowanoak Waste Services: Dudley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answers of 25 July 2017 to Questions 5342, 5394, 5395 and 5396, what the reasons are for the time taken by the Environment Agency to deal with the site operated by Rowan Oak Waste at Shaw Road in Dudley.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","8929"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757626","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-13","<p>We estimate that around 8 million dogs in the UK are microchipped, which represents about 94% of all dogs.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-13T13:25:59.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757626/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757626/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757626/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-05","Dogs: Registration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many and what proportion of dogs are registered as microchipped.","false","Biography information for John Spellar","Warley","John Spellar","8865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757627","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Government recognises the terrible impact of the theft of a family pet. The theft of a pet dog is already a criminal offence punishable by a maximum penalty of 7 years’ imprisonment.</p><p> </p><p>In order to make a direct link between a dog and its owner, to deter such thefts in the first place, and to increase the chances of an owner being re-united with their dog, it is a requirement that all dogs be identified by a microchip. Animal welfare bodies, veterinary organisations, local authorities and the police support the policy of compulsory dog microchipping.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-13T16:08:42.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757627/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757627/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757627/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-05","Dogs: Theft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of prevalence of dog theft in the UK; and what steps the Government is taking to tackle such theft.","false","Biography information for John Spellar","Warley","John Spellar","8861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757628","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-13","<p>The number of defendants proceeded against at magistrates’ courts for offences under the Microchipping of Dogs (England) Regulations 2015, from April to December 2016, can be viewed in the table (Annex 1).</p><p>Please see attached.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-13T13:33:12.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757628/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757628/answer","Annex 1 PQ 8866.doc","Annex 1","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757628/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-05","Dogs: Registration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many prosecutions there have been for failure to microchip a dog since April 2016.","false","Biography information for John Spellar","Warley","John Spellar","8866"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757629","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-18","<p>The Department does not hold expenditure data at the level of detail requested.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-18T15:32:58.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757629/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757629/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757629/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-05","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how much his Department has paid in letting fees for its estate in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757630","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-13","<p>UK Overseas Territory (OT) Governments are constitutionally responsible for the protection and conservation of their natural environments.</p><p> </p><p>Defra is currently providing over £99,000 through Darwin Plus for the development and implementation of a sustainable waste management strategy for Ascension Island, supported by the Waste and Resources Action Programme. We have also committed over £190,000 to increasing paper and cardboard recycling in St Helena.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-09-13T09:07:05.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757630/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757630/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757630/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-05","Recycling: British Overseas Territories","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what support his Department is providing to assist Overseas Territories for recycling.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","8545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757631","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-13","<p>There are several schemes which offer EU subsidies to farmers. The main scheme for direct subsidy is the Basic Payment Scheme (BPS) which replaced the Single Payment Scheme (SPS) in 2015. Figures below are for BPS and SPS.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Amount</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Amount</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p>Colne Valley</p></td><td><p>West Yorkshire</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>SPS</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>£1,206,660</p></td><td><p>£16,284,594</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>£1,099,675</p></td><td><p>£15,853,687</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>£1,032,367</p></td><td><p>£14,747,827</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>£1,038,170</p></td><td><p>£14,882,482</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>£904,551</p></td><td><p>£13,459,240</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>BPS</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>£979, 517</p></td><td><p>£13,016,020</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>£1,093,615</p></td><td><p>£14,338,213</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-13T11:33:59.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757631/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757631/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757631/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-05","Agriculture: West Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how much the EU paid in subsidies to farmers in (a) Colne Valley constituency and (b) West Yorkshire in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Thelma Walker","Colne Valley","Thelma Walker","8632"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757632","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Government is preparing to negotiate our exit from the European Union, and our new relationship with the EU should aim for the freest possible trade in goods and services between the United Kingdom and the EU.</p><p>The Rapid Alert System for Food and Feed is important currently in enabling the management of food and feed safety risks, providing early alerts of health or food contamination issues across the EU. At present this enables the UK to respond quickly to serious risks to public health relating to food and animal feed. The Government is considering the best approach for the management of notification of food and feed safety risks once we have left the EU. It will be our priority to maintain the UK’s high standards of food and feed safety.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-11T14:24:54.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757632/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757632/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757632/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Agricultural Products: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether it is the Government's policy to seek to continue membership of the Rapid Alert System for food and feed when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","8666"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757633","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-18","<p>The Department does not hold commercial sub-let data at the level of detail requested.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-18T15:14:42.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757633/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757633/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757633/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-05","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Sub-letting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how much his Department has received from sub-lets on its estate in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8736"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757634","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-13","<p>We do not collect data on the percentage of food packaging that is recyclable.</p><p>Packaging has an important and positive role to play in reducing product damage and minimising food waste. Keeping food fresher for longer through innovations such as vacuum packing and re-sealable packs has a significant impact on extending the life of products and reducing waste.</p><p>Great progress in reduction of food packaging has been made through the Courtauld commitment. Courtauld 3 signatories reduced food and packaging waste in the supply chain by 3% between 2012 and 2015, preventing 219,000 tonnes of waste and 555,000t of CO2e. Signatories to the Hospitality and Food Service Agreement reduced their food and packaging waste by 11% between 2012 and 2015, exceeding their 5% target.</p><p>This Government remains committed to preventing waste where possible and will be consulting widely on our plans for resources, waste and recycling in developing our waste and resources strategy.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-09-13T09:09:42.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757634/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757634/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757634/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-05","Food: Packaging","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps he is taking to reduce the use of plastic packaging for food.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","8711"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757635","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-18","<table><tbody><tr><td><p>Question</p></td><td><p>Timescale</p></td><td><p>Number of projects</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>a</p></td><td><p>Three to five months</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>b</p></td><td><p>Six months to 11 months</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>c</p></td><td><p>12 months to 23 months</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>d</p></td><td><p>24 months +</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The figures above include:</p><p> </p><ul><li><p>Procurement projects with a start date between 01 April 2014 and 06 September 2017 (a total of 815 procurements completed in this period)</p><p> </p></li><li><p>Procurements projects for Core Defra only</p><p> </p></li><li><p>Procurement projects above the OJEU (Official Journal of the European Union) limit. Currently this is set at £106,047 for central government departments.</p></li></ul><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-18T15:27:33.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757635/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757635/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757635/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-05","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many procurements undertaken by his Department have taken more than (a) three months, (b) six months, (c) one year and (d) two years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757636","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-13","<p>We do not collect data on the percentage of food packaging that is recyclable.</p><p>Packaging has an important and positive role to play in reducing product damage and minimising food waste. Keeping food fresher for longer through innovations such as vacuum packing and re-sealable packs has a significant impact on extending the life of products and reducing waste.</p><p>Great progress in reduction of food packaging has been made through the Courtauld commitment. Courtauld 3 signatories reduced food and packaging waste in the supply chain by 3% between 2012 and 2015, preventing 219,000 tonnes of waste and 555,000t of CO2e. Signatories to the Hospitality and Food Service Agreement reduced their food and packaging waste by 11% between 2012 and 2015, exceeding their 5% target.</p><p>This Government remains committed to preventing waste where possible and will be consulting widely on our plans for resources, waste and recycling in developing our waste and resources strategy.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-09-13T09:09:15.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757636/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757636/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757636/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-05","Food: Packaging","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what percentage of food packaging is recyclable.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","8710"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757637","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-25","<p>On Friday 21st July, the Government published the summary of responses to our consultation on plans to ban the manufacture and sale of cosmetics and personal care products containing microbeads. We notified our proposals under the Technical Standards Directive (EU) and the Technical Barriers to Trade Agreement (WTO) on 28 July. This stage in the process takes 3 months and will end on 28 October subject to there being no valid objections. We intend to introduce legislation later this year.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-09-25T13:21:30.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757637/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757637/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757637/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-05","Microplastics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when he plans to lay regulations on the use of microbeads.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","8789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757638","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>​The Foreign and Commonwealth Office's central contract databases do not hold this information for all procurements. Accordingly, providing the number of procurements for each given time period could only be completed at disproportionate cost.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-09-13T15:13:51.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757638/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757638/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757638/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many procurements undertaken by his Department have taken more than (a) three months, (b) six months, (c) one year and (d) two years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757639","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>​The UK Government has not seen conclusive evidence of a direct, significant link between the trade in illegal ivory and the financing of international terrorism. Recent research by the Royal United Services Institute tends to disputes previous claims that ivory is a major source of finance for global terrorist networks such as Al Shabab. This research suggests instead that organised crime and widespread corruption are a greater threat to endangered wildlife. The Government will continue to monitor reporting on the issue. Global terrorism and the illegal ivory trade are issues of serious concern to the UK Government and tackling both is a priority.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-09-13T15:00:10.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757639/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757639/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757639/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","Ivory: Terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the contribution made by trade in illegal ivory to the financing of international terrorism.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","8712"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757640","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>We have not received any income from sub-let leasehold properties on our UK estate since 2010.</p><p>We receive some income on our overseas estate from sub-letting leasehold properties but it would not be possible to provide the information requested without incurring disproportionate cost.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-12T09:14:15.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757640/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757640/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757640/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Sub-letting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much his Department has received from sub-lets on its estate in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8738"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757641","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>The UK invested £2.18 million to plan, prepare and deliver biometric voter registration in Somaliland. Over 870,000 people have registered, more than half are women. The UK is providing an additional £1.4 million in funding to support the broader Somaliland electoral cycle, including civic education.</p><p>The UK is also providing £202,017 to fund a 60-strong international election observation mission for the delayed Somaliland Presidential election, now scheduled for November 2017.</p><p>The UK confirmed on 26 January 2017 that no UK funding would be used to cover additional costs associated with electoral delays.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-09-11T14:11:00.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757641/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757641/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757641/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","Somaliland: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what funding the Government has provided to support the (a) operation and (b) monitoring of elections in Somaliland.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","8706"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757642","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>The UK is a long-standing supporter of the Organisation for Security and Co-operation in Europe (OSCE) and Special Monitoring Mission (SMM) to Ukraine. The UK contingent is the second largest in the Mission; we are one of the largest contributors to its budget, and have provided specialist training and support. We receive regular reports from the OSCE on the SMM's work. These highlight a worrying level of ongoing ceasefire violations in the Donbas, which continue to cause casualties on a daily basis. They also show persistent obstruction of monitors, in the vast majority of cases by Russian-backed separatists. SMM public reports can be found on the OSCE website.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-09-11T15:36:41.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757642/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757642/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757642/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","Ukraine: Organisation for Security and Cooperation in Europe","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent reports he has received from the Organisation for Security and Co-operation in Europe Special Monitoring Missions to Ukraine; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","8699"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757643","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>We regularly raise the importance of ensuring unrestricted humanitarian access with the Government of Saudi Arabia. The Foreign Secretary discussed this issue most recently with Saudi Foreign Minister Al Jubeir on 5 September. We call upon all parties to the conflict to improve humanitarian access to alleviate the suffering of the Yemeni people. The UK sponsored a UN Security Council Presidential Statement with words to that effect which was agreed on 15 June.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-11T16:58:05.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757643/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757643/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757643/answer","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757643/answer/previousversion/9965","Biography information for Alistair Burt","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","Yemen: International Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations the Government has made to the Government of Saudi Arabia on unrestricted humanitarian access to Yemen.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","8639"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757644","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-08","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office takes all credible reports of disappearances, political arrests, assassinations and government brutality in Rwanda seriously. The British High Commission in Kigali is closely monitoring the investigations into Diane Rigwara and her family following their recent detention. We remain concerned about the limited democratic space and constrained civil and political rights in Rwanda, and regularly raise these concerns with the Rwandan Government.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-09-08T11:48:05.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757644/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757644/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757644/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","Rwanda: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of the accuracy of reports of disappearances, political arrests and assassinations and government brutality in Rwanda.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","8625"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757645","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The British Government continues to discuss the situation in Rakhine with the Government of Burma. On 7 September, the Foreign Secretary called State Counsellor Aung San Suu Kyi to raise our strong concerns about Rakhine. They agreed any human rights abuses or violations must be investigated urgently. Our Ambassador continues to engage with officials from the Burmese Foreign Ministry on the full range of challenges facing Rakhine State.</p><p>On 30 August the UK convened a discussion on Burma at the UN Security Council. The UK urged the security forces in Rakhine to show restraint and called for all parties to de-escalate tensions. The Foreign Secretary released a statement on 2 September calling for an end to the violence. Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon made a statement at the 36th session of the Human Rights Council on 11 September which made clear that the UK strongly condemned the violence, and called on all parties to de-escalate tensions and address the humanitarian crisis</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-09-12T09:21:45.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757645/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757645/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757645/answer","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757645/answer/previousversion/9981","Biography information for Mark Field","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","Burma: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of (a) the security situation, (b) human rights and (c) religious freedom in the state of Rohingya, Burma.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","8605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757646","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>On 5 September I summoned the North Korean Ambassador to make clear the UK's condemnation of North Korea's nuclear test on 3 September. I emphasised that North Korea's reckless actions have created a deeply dangerous and unstable situation on the Korean peninsula. I urged the Ambassador to pass on this message to the regime in Pyongyang: it must end its illegal pursuit of nuclear and ballistic missiles and return to dialogue with the international community.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-09-11T15:20:44.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757646/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757646/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757646/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","North Korea: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with (a) his North Korean counterpart and (b) officials from the North Korean Government, since the North Korean nuclear missile test on 3 September 2017.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","8606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757647","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>​In her press statement of 8 April 2015, the ICC Prosecutor set out some of the complicated issues associated with any potential investigation of Daesh by the ICC. The UK fully respects the independence of the ICC Prosecutor in this matter. On 14 August 2017, the Government of Iraq wrote to the UN Secretary General, requesting support to hold Daesh accountable for their crimes. The UK is working with the UN Security Council to deliver this support.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-12T10:06:18.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757647/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757647/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757647/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","Islamic State: International Criminal Court","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make representations to the International Criminal Court to reconsider its decision not to open a preliminary examination into crimes committed by Daesh.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","8634"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757648","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The UK is a strong supporter of the International Criminal Court (ICC). As a state party to the Rome Statute the UK has a fully cooperative relationship with the ICC and regular discussions on a range of issues.</p><p>The UK encourages non-state parties to accede to the Rome Statute. We are happy to offer support to any State that is in the process of ratifying the Rome Statute or needs assistance in adopting the national legislation needed to enact the Rome Statute.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-12T10:01:06.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757648/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757648/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757648/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","Iraq: International Criminal Court","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make representations to the Government of Iraq to ratify the Rome Statue of the International Criminal Court.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","8635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757649","Department for International Development","false","2017-09-11","<p>UK aid policy in Rwanda has evolved considerably since 2009. The UK has not provided General Budget Support to Rwanda since 2013 and stopped Sector Budget Support in 2014. The British Government continues to speak candidly with the Government of Rwanda on all issues of human rights, freedom of expression and governance. Commonwealth membership is a matter for the Commonwealth Secretariat.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-09-11T15:56:45.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757649/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757649/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757649/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-05","Rwanda: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how the findings of the Commonwealth Human Rights Initiative report on Rwanda, published in 2009, have affected policy on (a) aid to Rwanda and (b) Rwanda's continued membership of the Commonwealth.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","8637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757650","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The British Government continues to discuss the situation in Rakhine with the Government of Burma. On 7 September, the Foreign Secretary called State Counsellor Aung San Suu Kyi to raise our strong concerns about Rakhine. They agreed any human rights abuses or violations must be investigated urgently. Our Ambassador continues to engage with officials from the Burmese Foreign Ministry on the full range of challenges facing Rakhine State.</p><p>On 30 August the UK convened a discussion on Burma at the UN Security Council. The UK urged the security forces in Rakhine to show restraint and called for all parties to de-escalate tensions. The Foreign Secretary released a statement on 2 September calling for an end to the violence. Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon made a statement at the 36th session of the Human Rights Council on 11 September which made clear that the UK strongly condemned the violence, and called on all parties to de-escalate tensions and address the humanitarian crisis.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-09-12T09:19:22.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757650/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757650/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757650/answer","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757650/answer/previousversion/9967","Biography information for Mark Field","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","Burma: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with (a) Aung San Suu Kyi and (b) officials from the Burmese Foreign Ministry on (i) the security situation, (ii) human rights and (iii) religious freedom in the state of Rohingya, Burma.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","8602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757651","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>​FCO ministers including myself have discussed LGBT rights and same-sex marriage with Australian counterparts in general terms. With the exception of marriage, LGBT people in Australia have the same rights and protections as anyone else. The question of whether same-sex marriage should be legalised in Australia is a matter for the Australian people to decide.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-09-11T15:18:54.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757651/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757651/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757651/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","Australia: LGBT People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he has discussed (a) LGBT rights and (b) same-sex marriage with his Australian counterpart.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","8603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757652","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>We are not aware of any letting fees on our UK estate since 2010.</p><p>Overseas, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office runs an estate in over 270 locations worldwide. It would not be possible to provide the information requested on overseas properties without incurring disproportionate cost.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-12T09:31:12.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757652/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757652/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757652/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much his Department has paid in letting fees for its estate in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757653","Department for International Development","false","2017-09-12","<p>In Kenya, the Department for International Development has supported development of Kenyan transport systems, including railways and roads, to improve the speed and efficiency of transport and trading routes. Financial disbursements have been as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>Total (£)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Amount (£)</p></td><td><p>3,900,000</p></td><td><p>14,600,000</p></td><td><p>6,500,000</p></td><td><p>16,700,000</p></td><td><p>41,700,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-09-12T17:02:29.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757653/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757653/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757653/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-05","Kenya: Infrastructure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assistance the Government has given to Kenya for infrastructure, railways and roads in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","8727"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757654","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>Her Majesty's Government promotes Freedom of Religion or Belief (FoRB) in many countries through diplomatic channels, public statements and support for projects to promote tolerance. A small selection of examples of steps Her Majesty's Government has taken recently to tackle and condemn religious persecution is provided below. It would place a disproportionate burden on resources to produce an exhaustive list of all recent actions taken by Foreign and Commonwealth Office officials abroad in this area.</p><p>During his recent visit to Bangladesh, Lord Ahmad visited an Ahmadiyya mosque where he spoke publicly of the importance of religious tolerance. In the wake of recent attacks against Coptic Christians in Egypt, the Foreign Secretary made a statement condemning religious intolerance and violence against religious minorities. We have issued a number of statements in response to Russia's Supreme Court ruling banning Jehovah's Witnesses as 'extremists'. Officials from our Embassy in Moscow have attended court hearings and continue to monitor this case closely. In Eritrea, we have continued to call on the Government to release all prisoners detained without due process, including those detained for their religious beliefs. And in Sudan, we lobbied consistently on behalf of four imprisoned Christian pastors (now released – partly, we judge, as a result of our efforts).</p><p>At the United Nations Human Rights Council we continue to work to sustain consensus on the adoption and implementation of the European Union sponsored Resolution on 'Freedom of Religion or Belief' and the Organisation for Islamic Cooperation sponsored Resolution on 'Combating Religious Intolerance'. We also continue to support a number of projects to promote tolerance through the FCO's Magna Carta Fund, including a project to promote legal and social protection of FoRB in secondary school curricula across the Middle East and North Africa.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-09-13T16:03:58.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757654/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757654/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757654/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent steps he has taken to tackle religious persecution abroad.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","8795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757655","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>​</p><p>The UK Government is deeply committed to the achievement of UN Sustainable Development Goal 8.7, which calls, among other things, for the global eradication of forced labour, modern slavery and human trafficking by 2030. Although I have not directly discussed the specific issue of trafficking in women with my counterparts in China and Vietnam, as part of our efforts to achieve this target, Ministers and officials from the FCO and other relevant Government Departments have been actively engaged with China and Vietnam on the wider modern slavery and human trafficking agenda.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-09-13T15:53:38.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757655/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757655/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757655/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","China and Vietnam: Human Trafficking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his counterparts in China and Vietnam on curtailing the trafficking of women.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","8726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757656","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Government works with Nigerian law enforcement agencies involved in investigating and prosecuting the perpetrators of modern slavery. This includes building relationships and providing training and equipment. In July 2016 the Prime Minister announced a £33.5 million fund to tackle modern slavery, of which £5 million has been allocated to Nigeria. It will be used to improve the effectiveness of law enforcement agencies, raise awareness amongst would-be victims and perpetrators of the consequences of modern slavery and the penalties for involvement, and to help safeguard victims and witnesses through comprehensive support packages. During their visit to Nigeria, the Foreign Secretary and the International Development Secretary announced a further £7 million of support over the next three years. This will be used to help develop alternative livelihoods options for communities in areas where trafficking occurs, and to help victims of trafficking recover and reintegrate into their communities. It will also fund research on the causes of trafficking and modern slavery.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-09-13T16:23:00.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757656/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757656/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757656/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","Nigeria: Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how the Government plans to monitor and support the Nigerian Government in tackling modern day slavery and human trafficking.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","8871"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757657","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>The UK is working closely with the Nigerian Government in tackling Boko Haram and promoting peace in the North East by providing a substantial package of military, intelligence and development support. This includes training for the Nigerian armed forces, supporting Nigerian intelligence analysis, and £5 million to support the Multinational Joint Task Force, the regional military force tackling Boko Haram. We have also increased counter-terrorism cooperation, providing training on response to terrorist attacks and bomb scene management. During their recent visit to Nigeria, the Foreign Secretary and International Development Secretary announced an additional £200 million of humanitarian aid over the next four years.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-09-13T16:13:54.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757657/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757657/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757657/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","Nigeria: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what coordinated and joint actions the Government plans to undertake with the Nigerian Government to tackle insurgency and promote peace in North East Nigeria.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","8873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757658","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to the statement made by my Rt Hon Friend the Foreign Secretary (<a href="https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2017-09-05/debates/C42A1D96-73C1-4D71-883E-BC8F83842285/KoreanPeninsula" target="_blank">https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2017-09-05/debates/C42A1D96-73C1-4D71-883E-BC8F83842285/KoreanPeninsula</a>)</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-09-13T16:07:14.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757658/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757658/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757658/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","North Korea: Guided Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with the Governments of (a) Japan, (b) South Korea and (c) the US since the launch of an intermediate range ballistic missile by North Korea on 29 August 2017.","false","Biography information for Paul Masterton","East Renfrewshire","Paul Masterton","8900"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757659","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>As the Foreign Secretary made clear in his statement (<a href="https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2017-09-05/debates/C42A1D96-73C1-4D71-883E-BC8F83842285/KoreanPeninsula" target="_blank">https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2017-09-05/debates/C42A1D96-73C1-4D71-883E-BC8F83842285/KoreanPeninsula</a>), it is crucial that the international community maintains pressure on the North Korean regime, both diplomatically and through sanctions. Measures against the financial sector and commodity exports make it harder for the DPRK to fund its illegal programmes. The unanimous adoption of UNSCRs 2371 on 5 August and UNSCR 2375 on 11 September, with the toughest package of sanctions on DPRK yet, demonstrates the level of consensus among the international community on this issue.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-09-13T16:19:02.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757659/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757659/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757659/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","North Korea: Sanctions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment his Department has made of the effectiveness of the UN sanctions regime against North Korea.","false","Biography information for Paul Masterton","East Renfrewshire","Paul Masterton","8901"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757660","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>The UK Government is deeply concerned at the actions of the North Korean regime, which is subject to stringent UN sanctions. Such transfers to Syria or another country would be very serious. Transfers of chemicals to Syria would be of particular concern given the Syrian regime's record of using chemical weapons. The UN Panel of Experts investigate any potential breaches of UN sanctions brought to their attention.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-13T15:46:00.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757660/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757660/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757660/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","North Korea: Chemical Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports his Department has received on allegations that North Korea has been taking an active role as a proliferator of weapons of mass destruction by attempting to supply chemicals to the Syrian Government; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Paul Masterton","East Renfrewshire","Paul Masterton","8899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757661","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>While the UK Government fully supports the Republic of Korea's right to defend itself, the decision on the installation of the THAAD missile system is for the Korean government and other partners. At a United Nations Security Council emergency session on 4 September, every member, including China and Russia, denounced the 3 September nuclear test by the Democratic People's Republic of Korea.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-09-13T16:05:45.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757661/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757661/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757661/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","South Korea: Ballistic Missile Defence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the Government's position is on the installation of the US Administration's THAAD missile system on South Korean territory.","false","Biography information for Paul Masterton","East Renfrewshire","Paul Masterton","8898"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757662","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>The right to freedom of religion is enshrined in the Nepali Constitution of September 2015. However, we have concerns regarding the drafting of the new legislation on religious conversion, which could be interpreted in a way that would limit people’s rights to express their religion and, potentially, their right to choose their religion.</p><p>Our Embassy in Kathmandu has consistently encouraged the Government of Nepal and members of Nepal’s parliament to ensure Nepal meets its international human rights obligations. This includes ensuring the protection of the right to change religion. My officials have met with representatives from religious minorities to better understand their concerns. My predecessor, My. Hon Friend the member for Reading West (Mr Sharma), also discussed human rights with Nepali Foreign Minister Mahat at the UN on 22 September 2016. We continue to do so.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-09-11T15:33:00.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757662/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757662/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757662/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","Nepal: Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make representations to his Nepalese counterpart on freedom of religious conscience and people who wish to convert from one religion to another in that country.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","8883"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757663","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The UK Government strongly supports the right to freedom of religion or belief. Saudi Arabia remains a Foreign and Commonwealth Office human rights priority country due to restrictions on the freedom of religion or belief and we raise this at every appropriate opportunity.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-12T10:03:22.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757663/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757663/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757663/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","Saudi Arabia: Antisemitism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his counterparts in Saudia Arabia on antisemitism.","false","Biography information for Sir Graham Brady","Altrincham and Sale West","Mr Graham Brady","8844"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757664","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>​There have been a number of recent protests targeting synagogues in Turkey, reportedly in response to the situation at the Al Aqsa mosque in East Jerusalem in July. These were condemned by both President Erdoğan and Prime Minister Yıldırım, who emphasised the importance of freedom of religion. As a friend and ally of Turkey, the UK has a frank and honest dialogue with the Turkish authorities on a range of issues, including freedom of religion and non-discrimination.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-09-13T15:15:07.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757664/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757664/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757664/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","Turkey: Antisemitism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with Turkish counterparts on antisemitism.","false","Biography information for Sir Graham Brady","Altrincham and Sale West","Mr Graham Brady","8842"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757665","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>​The Foreign Secretary has not had any recent discussions with his counterparts in Latvia and Lithuania on Holocaust revisionism. They meet regularly to discuss the full range of bilateral issues. Our Embassies in Latvia and Lithuania attend ceremonies remembering the victims of the Holocaust.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-09-13T15:17:11.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757665/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757665/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757665/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","Latvia and Lithuania: World War II","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his counterparts in Latvia and Lithuania on Holocaust revisionism.","false","Biography information for Sir Graham Brady","Altrincham and Sale West","Mr Graham Brady","8843"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757666","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The British Government opposes the use of the death penalty in all circumstances and takes any allegations of extrajudicial killings seriously. Whilst at present we have no plans to raise the 1988 executions, we continue to take action with the international community by pressing for improvements on all human rights issues in Iran, including ending the death penalty, and by supporting the work done by the Special Rapporteur.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-12T08:56:22.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757666/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757666/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757666/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","Iran: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his Iranian counterparts on the report to the 34th Session of the UN Human Rights Council by Ms Asma Jahaigir, on human rights violations in that country in 1988.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","8957"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757667","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Government is deeply concerned by the crisis in South Sudan. We continue to work with partners to lead the international response, and encourage all sides to bring an end to conflict, allow humanitarian access, and return to an inclusive political process.</p><p>We are strongly encouraging all sides to respond constructively to the recent initiative led by the Intergovernmental Authority on Development to revitalise the peace process. The immediate priority must be a negotiated ceasefire and a peace process that facilitates the participation of non-armed actors. We also continue to lobby the government of South Sudan to allow the UN Mission in South Sudan to effectively fulfil its mandate, and for the swift deployment of the Regional Protection Force.</p><p>The UK is one of the largest humanitarian donors to South Sudan, and spent £168 million through our bilateral aid programme in 2016/17. This year we are continuing to provide a package of support.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-09-13T15:50:47.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757667/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757667/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757667/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","South Sudan: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the political situation in South Sudan; and what steps is he making to support the peace process in that country.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","8958"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757668","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>​The UK is concerned by the human rights situation in Yemen and takes allegations of violations against international humanitarian law very seriously. The UK's position is that it is first and foremost the responsibility of the parties themselves to investigate allegations and take action.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-11T17:02:12.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757668/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757668/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757668/answer","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757668/answer/previousversion/9970","Biography information for Alistair Burt","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","Yemen: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if the Government will support the Dutch Government initiative to create an international investigation into the alleged violations and abuses of human rights and international humanitarian law in Yemen at the 36th session of the UN Human Rights Council; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","8921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757669","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>North Korea's recent actions are reckless and pose an unacceptable threat to the international community. The UK will work with our partners and allies to tackle this threat.</p><p>We welcome China's condemnation of North korea's activity. China has supported all UNSCRs, including the most recent, UNSCR 2371 and UNSCR 2375. As the Foreign Secretary said on 5 September, in a statement to Parliament on the situation on the Korean Peninsula, China has a unique ability to influence the regime. The Foreign Secretary spoke to the Chinese Foreign Minister on 4 August and 1 September to urge China to use its influence on the DPRK regime and implement sanctions fully. The Foreign Secretary had already urged China to support further action at the UN Security Council in a statement on 4 July. As The Minister for Asia and the Pacific, I also discussed North Korea with the Chinese government during my visit to Beijing in the final week of August.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-09-13T16:21:51.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757669/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757669/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757669/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","North Korea: Sanctions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations his Department has made to the Government of China on the enforcement of existing UN sanctions against North Korea.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","8906"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757670","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>Following the recent outbreak in violence in Rakhine State, the Foreign Secretary has spoken with State Counsellor Aung San Suu Kyi and has raised our concerns. Our Ambassador in Rangoon has also raised these issues in several occasions. The Minister of State for International Development, my Rt Hon Friend Alistair Burt MP, visited Burma in July. He discussed the situation in Rakhine State with the Burmese Ministers of Health and Education and met Rohingya leaders.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-09-13T16:24:53.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757670/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757670/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757670/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-05","Burma: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations his Department has made to the Government of the Republic of the Union of Myanmar on the treatment of the Rohingya people.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","8984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757671","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>NHS Digital collects and regularly published publically available data on detention under the Mental Health Act. However information is not available in the format requested.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-09-11T15:28:25.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757671/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757671/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757671/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Compulsorily Detained Psychiatric Patients","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people were detained on a Short Term Detention Order under the Mental Health Act 1983 in each year since 2010; and what the ages were of those people.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","8977"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757672","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>The data collected on detentions under the Mental Health Act are not collected by person, therefore the information is not possible to provide in the format requested.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-09-11T14:34:01.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757672/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757672/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757672/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Compulsorily Detained Psychiatric Patients","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people were detained under the Mental Health Act 1983 in each year since 2010 broken down for each section of the Act under which they were held.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","8978"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757673","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-11T13:11:31.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757673/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757673/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757673/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Primary Biliary Cirrhosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people have been diagnosed with primary biliary cholangitis in each of the last five years by age.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","8919"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757674","Department of Health","false","2017-09-13","<p>The average costs in an elderly residential care home in the private and public sector are below</p><p> </p><p>- Residential care for age 65+, external provision: £534 per week in 2015/16;</p><p>- Residential care for age 65+, in house provision: £789 per week in 2015/16; and</p><p>- The data suggests that only 5.7% of local authority funded age 65+ residential care weeks were in in-house facilities.</p><p> </p><p>The source is:</p><p><a href="http://www.content.digital.nhs.uk/catalogue/PUB22240" target="_blank">http://www.content.digital.nhs.uk/catalogue/PUB22240</a></p><p>The Department does not hold any data on average life expectancy of elderly residents in care homes – however the Department does hold published data on a resident’s length of stay in a care home where a service user’s stay ends due to their death. While this is occasionally used as a measure for life expectancy, this does not record stays for individuals in care homes where their stay ended because they moved from one home to another.</p><p>The statistics show that the average length of stay in a single residential care home in England that ended in a service users’ death was around 26 months, although this statistic does not include any previous stays in other homes.</p><p>The published source is:</p><p><a href="http://www.pssru.ac.uk/archive/pdf/3211.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.pssru.ac.uk/archive/pdf/3211.pdf</a></p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","8938","2017-09-13T15:44:50.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757674/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757674/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757674/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Care Homes: Life Expectancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the average life expectancy is of an elderly resident in a care home.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","8937"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757675","Department of Health","false","2017-09-13","<p>The average costs in an elderly residential care home in the private and public sector are below</p><p> </p><p>- Residential care for age 65+, external provision: £534 per week in 2015/16;</p><p>- Residential care for age 65+, in house provision: £789 per week in 2015/16; and</p><p>- The data suggests that only 5.7% of local authority funded age 65+ residential care weeks were in in-house facilities.</p><p> </p><p>The source is:</p><p><a href="http://www.content.digital.nhs.uk/catalogue/PUB22240" target="_blank">http://www.content.digital.nhs.uk/catalogue/PUB22240</a></p><p>The Department does not hold any data on average life expectancy of elderly residents in care homes – however the Department does hold published data on a resident’s length of stay in a care home where a service user’s stay ends due to their death. While this is occasionally used as a measure for life expectancy, this does not record stays for individuals in care homes where their stay ended because they moved from one home to another.</p><p>The statistics show that the average length of stay in a single residential care home in England that ended in a service users’ death was around 26 months, although this statistic does not include any previous stays in other homes.</p><p>The published source is:</p><p><a href="http://www.pssru.ac.uk/archive/pdf/3211.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.pssru.ac.uk/archive/pdf/3211.pdf</a></p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","8937","2017-09-13T15:44:50.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757675/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757675/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757675/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Care Homes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the average cost of an elderly residential care home is in the (a) private and (b) public sector.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","8938"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757676","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>Project Phoenix, the proposal to establish a new Public Private Partnership model for NHS infrastructure planning and investment, has being developed by Community Health Partnerships Ltd at the request of the Department. A business case for taking forward Project Phoenix is currently under development by the Department.</p><p> </p><p>Subject to its approval the business case will be made publicly available.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-09-11T14:47:46.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757676/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757676/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757676/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","NHS: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he plans to sign off the business case for NHS England's Project Phoenix; and if he will publish that business case.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","8922"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757677","Department of Health","false","2017-09-14","<p>Clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) are responsible for the provision of hearing aids for mild to moderate hearing loss within their local population. As with other services CCGs commission, they should take into consideration assessments of local need and any relevant guidance.</p><p> </p><p>To help inform and support commissioners in making local decisions, NHS England published, in July 2016, ‘Commissioning services for people with hearing loss: A framework for clinical commissioning groups’. The Framework acknowledges the benefits of addressing hearing loss in the prevention of conditions such as dementia.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-09-14T14:36:02.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757677/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757677/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757677/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Dementia: Hearing Aids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the Lancet Commission's recommendations on hearing loss in the report on dementia prevention, intervention and care, published in July 2017, what assessment he has made of the effect on dementia prevention proposals to restrict hearing aid provision for those with mild or moderate hearing loss.","false","Biography information for Bambos Charalambous","Enfield, Southgate","Bambos Charalambous","8968"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757678","Department of Health","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Department continues to work with our delivery partner, Skills for Care, to encourage recruitment into the sector, and to provide multiple entry points and attractive career pathways.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is also working to improve the domestic supply of nurses. This includes the development of new routes into nursing such as the new Nursing Associate role and the Nursing Degree Apprenticeship. The new Nursing Degree Apprenticeship once established could result in up to 1,000 domestic apprentice nurses each year.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-09-13T15:49:20.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757678/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757678/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757678/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Care Homes: Labour Turnover","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he plans to take to improve the recruitment and retention of care assistants in (a) nursing and (b) residential homes.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","8939"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757679","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>Public Health England is due to publish an outbreak report within two weeks. In addition, an article is also scheduled to be published in Eurosurveillance on 7 September 2017.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-11T14:17:15.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757679/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757679/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757679/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","E. coli: Dorset","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 5 September 2017 to Question 5841, on E. coli: Dorset, from which reports the information given is based; and if he will place copies of those reports in the Library.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","8972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757680","Department of Health","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Department does not issue guidance to hospitals or clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) on the criteria for access to particular clinical services. NHS England provides guidance to CCGs which are primarily responsible for commissioning services to meet the requirements of their population. In doing so, CCGs need to ensure that the services they provide are fit for purpose, reflect the needs of the local population, and are based on the available evidence. CCGs should take national guidelines into account as they take commissioning decisions.</p><p>It is the role of the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence and NHS England (alongside other arm’s length bodies) to issue guidance to CCGs, based on the latest evidence and expertise.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-13T16:20:29.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757680/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757680/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757680/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Joint Replacements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what guidelines his Department issues to hospitals and clinical commissioning groups on criteria for hip and knee replacements.","false","Biography information for John Spellar","Warley","John Spellar","8859"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757681","Department of Health","false","2017-09-13","<p>There are no specific National Health Service guidelines that cover withdrawal from prescription drugs in general. However the recently-updated National Clinical Guidelines for Drug Misuse and dependence has specific guidance about pharmacological management of dependence on benzodiazepines and z-drugs, including prescribing regimens, detoxification, adjunctive therapies and monitoring. The guidelines are available at the link below:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/628634/clinical_guidelines_2017.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/628634/clinical_guidelines_2017.pdf</a> (starts at page 119)</p><p> </p><p>Addiction to prescribed and over the counter medicines is a concern and it is essential that people only take these medicines in accordance with advice from a health professional. People who feel that they might be dependent on either prescribed or over the counter medicines should seek help from a health professional in the first instance (such as a general practitioner or pharmacist).</p><p> </p><p>Local authorities are supported by Public Health England to develop tailored responses to existing and emerging drug misuse in their area and, in conjunction with the NHS, to address specific concerns about addiction to prescribed and over the counter medicines.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-13T16:19:37.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757681/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757681/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757681/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Prescription Drugs: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the NHS guidelines are for rates of withdrawal for prescription drug addiction.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","8875"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757682","Department of Health","false","2017-09-13","<p>There have been no recent discussions with devolved administrations on access to National Health Service patient records. Access to patient records in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland is a matter for devolved administrations. General practitioner practices in England have been required to offer online access to their patients’ detailed coded records since 1 April 2016. This includes items such as allergies, adverse reactions, medications, test results, problems and diagnoses and immunisations.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-09-13T15:58:13.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757682/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757682/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757682/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Medical Records: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what (a) recent discussions he has had with Health ministers in the devolved governments and (b) progress has been made on ensuring full access to NHS patient records in all constituent parts of the UK.","false","Biography information for Stephen Crabb","Preseli Pembrokeshire","Stephen Crabb","8912"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757683","Department of Health","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Department understands that NHS Improvement is looking into a means of capturing hand hygiene data and compliance within the National Health Service.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-09-13T10:51:11.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757683/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757683/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757683/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Hospitals: Hygiene","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans his Department has to publish information on hospital hand hygiene compliance.","false","Biography information for Nigel Mills","Amber Valley","Nigel Mills","8915"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757684","Department of Health","false","2017-09-13","<p>The United Kingdom supported the “Improving the prevention, diagnosis and clinical management of sepsis” resolution adopted by the World Health Organization at the 70th World Health Assembly in May 2017.</p><p> </p><p>The Health and Social Care Act 2008: Code of Practice on the prevention and control of infections and related guidance was updated in 2015. The Department published a revised code of practice setting good practice on hand hygiene compliance. The code is used by the Care Quality Commission for inspections of health and social care services in England and underpins their regulatory activities.</p><p> </p><p>The UK works with international partners to support initiatives in infection prevention and management.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-09-13T10:45:48.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757684/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757684/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757684/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Sepsis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he plans to take to support the 70th World Health Assembly's resolution on improving hand hygiene and the prevention, diagnosis and clinical management of sepsis.","false","Biography information for Nigel Mills","Amber Valley","Nigel Mills","8914"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757686","Department of Health","true","2017-09-13","<p>Protection against measles is provided in the combination measles, mumps and rubella vaccine (MMR).</p><p>The latest <del class="ministerial">England</del> vaccine coverage figures <ins class="ministerial">for the United Kingdom</ins> (January to March 2017) show that uptake of one dose of MMR vaccine at two years was 91.7% and at five years was 95.4%, exceeding the World Health Organisation’s elimination target. Uptake of two MMR doses at five years was 88.1%.</p><p> </p><p>In November 2016, a measles and rubella elimination strategy group was established to oversee the development of a United Kingdom-wide Measles and Rubella elimination strategy. This strategy will focus on sustaining very high coverage of MMR in children below five years of age and on providing opportunities for MMR catch-up to older population groups at risk for measles and/or rubella. Public Health England (PHE) continues to work with others to supply information for health professionals and the public on the benefits and risks associated with MMR.</p><p> </p><p>PHE and NHS England work closely with providers at a local level to target specific communities where uptake of the MMR vaccine is known to be poor.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-13T15:11:29.407Z","2017-09-15T14:52:33.827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757686/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757686/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757686/answer","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757686/answer/previousversion/11365","Biography information for Steve Brine","17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Measles: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the immunisation rate is for measles; and what steps the Government is taking to improve measles immunisation coverage.","false","Biography information for John Spellar","Warley","John Spellar","8870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757687","Department of Health","false","2017-09-13","<p>NHS England is currently preparing to procure a network of genomic laboratory hubs. A full service specification will be issued at the start of the formal procurement process that will set out the requirements for the future informatics and data infrastructure, including the storage of genetic data.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-09-13T15:45:48.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757687/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757687/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757687/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Genetics: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans his Department has to issue technology guidelines to the new regional genetics laboratories in England on the storage of genetic data.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","8801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757688","Department of Health","false","2017-09-13","<p>NHS England currently commissions genetic testing for National Health Service patients in England from 23 genetic laboratories. NHS England has no knowledge of the centralisation of funding for NHS genetic testing in Cambridge that is being referred to. Whole genome sequencing is being carried out in Cambridge by Illumina for the 100,000 Genomes Project.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-09-13T15:46:53.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757688/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757688/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757688/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Genetics: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans he has for the future provision of genome testing in Newcastle following the decision to centralise genomic testing in Cambridge.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","8800"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757689","Department of Health","false","2017-09-13","<p>NHS England has no knowledge of the decision to centralise all National Health Service genomic testing in Cambridge that is being referred to and therefore no assessment has been made. Whole genome sequencing is being carried out in Cambridge by Illumina for the 100,000 Genomes Project.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-09-13T15:47:48.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757689/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757689/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757689/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Genetics: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of trends in the level of employment in (a) Cambridge and (b) the rest of the UK as a result of the decision to centralise genome testing in Cambridge.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","8802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757690","Department of Health","false","2017-09-13","<p>Since March 2017, Public Health England (PHE) has instigated a specific programme of engagement with all of the food industry (retailers and manufacturers) and this has included businesses that provide the food purchased and consumed out of home (such as coffee and sandwich shops). This engagement has focussed on encouraging industry to reformulate products to reduce their sugar content, as part of the wider sugar reduction programme set out in ‘Childhood obesity: a plan for action'. The issues discussed at these meetings have included the expectation that businesses will undertake work to meet the 20% reduction in sugar by 2020, and has covered businesses’ achievements to date and discussion of any technical challenges faced in terms of making current and future changes.</p><p> </p><p>Further discussions will continue to take place over the coming months to ensure that these businesses play their role in helping to reduce sugar consumption. A list of PHE’s industry and other stakeholder engagement on this agenda was published in March and can be viewed here:</p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sugar-reduction-and-wider-reformulation-stakeholder-engagement" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/sugar-reduction-and-wider-reformulation-stakeholder-engagement</a></p><p> </p><p>Further updates on engagement will also be published at regular intervals.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-13T15:09:43.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757690/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757690/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757690/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Coffee: Sugar","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions his Department has had with coffee companies on reformulating products to reduce their sugar content.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","8796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757691","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>No final decision has been taken yet on the sensitivity threshold for the faecal immunochemical test on its introduction to the bowel cancer screening programme from April 2018.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England is working with partners in Public Health England and the Department to inform this decision and is working through its regional teams to assess capacity in relation to a number of thresholds. The Department is confirming the process for decision making, which is likely to conclude this autumn.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-11T14:23:13.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757691/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757691/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757691/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Bowel Cancer: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether a decision has been made on what sensitivity threshold the faecal immunochemical test will be set at when it is introduced into the bowel cancer screening programme; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","8797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757692","Department of Health","false","2017-09-13","<p>NHS England is currently preparing to procure a network of genomic laboratory hubs. A full service specification will be issued at the start of the formal procurement process that will set out the requirements for the future informatics infrastructure.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-09-13T15:56:25.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757692/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757692/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757692/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Genetics: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what additional funding has been made available for the new regional genetic testing centres for IT infrastructure to exchange and store genetic testing data.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","8798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757693","Department of Health","false","2017-09-08","<p>We are not aware of any discussions on the potential efficacy of yoga for cancer patients. However, in December 2016, NHS England announced that over £200 million would be made available to Cancer Alliances over the next two years to improve earlier diagnosis and support roll out of the Recovery Package and Stratified follow-up pathways. The Recovery Package has been designed so that patients receive personalised care and support from the point they are diagnosed to improve their quality of life. This includes health and wellbeing events or similar giving patients access to information about complementary therapies and how these may help to facilitate wellbeing. Stratified follow-up pathways allow a more personalised approach to follow-up care after treatment, providing a better experience for patients.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-08T11:43:59.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757693/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757693/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757693/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Cancer: Yoga","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with the Royal College of Nursing and other professional medical bodies on the potential efficacy of yoga for cancer sufferers.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","8724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757694","Department of Health","false","2017-09-13","<p>NHS England has no knowledge of the decision to centralise all National Health Service genomic testing in Cambridge that is being referred to and therefore no assessment has been made. Whole genome sequencing is being carried out in Cambridge by Illumina for the 100,000 Genomes Project.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-09-13T15:39:39.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757694/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757694/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757694/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Genetics: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment has been made of the effect on local NHS services of centralising genomic testing in Cambridge.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","8799"
