"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757716","Department of Health","false","2017-09-13","<p>NHS England’s Clinical Priorities Advisory Group (CPAG) plans to meet in November 2017 and again in May 2018 to form its recommendations to NHS England’s Specialised Commissioning Oversight Group, which in turn makes recommendations to Specialised Services Commissioning Committee on funding for 2018/19.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the second round of its 2018/19 prioritisation process for specialised services NHS England's will consider all new or revised policy propositions eligible for consideration that have been developed in line with the published ‘Methods’ document, which sets out how CPAG would make future investment decisions. This approach ensures that policy proposals are developed by clinical leaders, reflect available evidence on clinical effectiveness, consider feedback from stakeholders and the public, and have been consistently costed to allow relative prioritisation.</p><p> </p><p>So far, nine policy proposals along with seven service specification proposals are currently scheduled for consideration at the November meeting of NHS England’s CPAG meeting. Policy propositions would need to be submitted by 9 October 2017 for consideration at the November Clinical CPAG meeting. The deadline for completed policy propositions for the planned May 2018 CPAG meeting has not yet been set.</p><p> </p><p>Any entirely new policy proposals would need to be considered as a potential service development for 2019/20.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England publishes details of the clinical commissioning policies being developed and/or revised. Further details on NHS England’s service development process and prioritisation process are available on NHS England’s website:</p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/</a></p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","8613 ; 8614 ; 8615 ; 8616","2017-09-13T16:36:13.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757716/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757716/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757716/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what deadline NHS England has set for submissions of new policy proposals to be considered as part of the second round of its 2018-19 prioritisation process for specialised services.","false","Biography information for Crispin Blunt","Reigate","Crispin Blunt","8617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757717","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>It is the responsibility of each clinical commissioning group’s Remuneration Committee to set appropriate pay rates for members of their governing bodies in accordance with the Clinical Commissioning Group Constitution and NHS England guidance.<sup>1</sup></p><p> </p><p>Note: <sup>1</sup><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/resources/resources-for-ccgs/#governance" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/resources/resources-for-ccgs/#governance</a></p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-11T14:20:58.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757717/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757717/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757717/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Clinical Commissioning Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the recommended level of stipend is to be paid to members of governing bodies of clinical commissioning groups.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","8697"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757718","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>A new ‘front door streaming’ service has been in place at the emergency department at Arrowe Park Hospital since 4 September 2017. This new service is expected to ensure that people with serious or life threatening conditions are seen and treated more quickly in the emergency department to improve the safety and quality of services and overall performance.</p><p> </p><p>To support this, Wirral Clinical Commissioning Group has increased the number of clinical staff working at the Arrowe Park Walk-in Centre by relocating staff from the former Eastham Clinic Walk-in Centre.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-09-11T13:07:19.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757718/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757718/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757718/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","NHS Walk-in Centres: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of closing Eastham walk-in centre on the volume of patients at the accident and emergency department at Arrowe Park Hospital.","false","Biography information for Alison McGovern","Wirral South","Alison McGovern","8671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757719","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Department has not sub-let any of its estate since 2010.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-09-11T13:31:08.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757719/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757719/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757719/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Department of Health: Sub-letting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much his Department has received from sub-lets on its estate in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8739"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757720","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>On 1 August 2017 the Government changed the funding system for pre-registration nurse training from National Health Service-funded tuition and bursaries to the standard student support system. NHS tuition and bursaries are paid from general taxation and therefore placed an artificial cap on the number of training places available.</p><p> </p><p>This change means we have moved away from centrally imposed number controls and financial limitations and therefore the artificial cap has been removed. We expect that these reforms will enable universities to offer up to an additional 10,000 training places by 2020, for nurses, midwives and allied health profession students.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-09-11T14:35:31.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757720/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757720/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757720/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Nurses: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he plans to remove the cap on nurse training; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","8696"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757721","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>No assessment has been made. The Department currently has no plans to change the list of medical conditions which provide for exemption from prescription charges because arrangements exist to ensure that prescriptions are affordable for everyone. However, a broad range of prescription charge exemptions are in place, for which someone who has been prescribed anti-psychotic medication may qualify. To support those with greatest need who do not qualify for an exemption, prescription prepayment certificates are available. A holder of a 12 month certificate can get all the prescriptions they need for just £2 per week.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-11T14:19:19.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757721/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757721/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757721/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Mental Illness: Prescription Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the proportion of patients on anti-psychotic medications who do not always take their medication due to the cost of prescriptions; and what consideration his Department has given to making such prescriptions free of charge.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","8674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757722","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>Information about which general practitioner practices are owned, rented or leased is not routinely collected by NHS England.</p><p> </p><p>Total investment in general practice premises for 2016/17 is due for publication by NHS Digital on 20 September, and will include all rent reimbursement and other premises-related costs for general practice in England.</p><p> </p><p>The recent independent report by Sir Robert Naylor highlighted the need to improve data on the primary care estate. The Government will set out its response to the report’s recommendations shortly.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-11T15:22:09.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757722/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757722/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757722/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","GP Surgeries: Rents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many and what proportion of premises in which NHS primary care is provided are privately owned and rented to GPs; and what the total amount of rent paid each year is for those premises.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","8728"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757723","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>In a Written Ministerial Statement on 7 September, the Department announced that NHS Professionals will remain in wholly public ownership. After careful consideration, the Government has concluded that none of the offers received for NHS Professionals through the open, rigorous bidding process conducted reflected the company’s growing potential and improved performance.</p><p> </p><p>Since the decision was taken to seek offers, NHS Professionals has significantly increased its performance such that audited profit before tax for the year ended 31 March 2017 was 44% higher than in the previous year. This improvement in financial performance continues to be built upon in the first quarter of the current year. The company’s improved financial and operational performance means it can now invest in improved IT infrastructure, expand its services to the National Health Service and transform into a world-class provider of flexible staff whilst remaining under public ownership – generating further savings for the NHS, all of which will continue to be reinvested in frontline services.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-09-11T14:12:13.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757723/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757723/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757723/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","NHS Professionals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent progress has been made on the sale of NHS Professionals.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","8729"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757724","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>NHS England and Health Education England (HEE) are working together with the profession to increase the general practitioner (GP) workforce. This includes measures to boost recruitment into general practice, address the reasons why GPs are leaving the profession, and encourage GPs to return to practice.</p><p> </p><p>HEE has implemented a range of improvements to increase the number of GP training places to 3,250 each year. In 2016 3,019 new starters were recruited to training posts – this is the highest number of GP trainees ever.</p><p> </p><p>In August 2017, NHS England announced plans to accelerate its international recruitment programme, following a series of successful regional pilots. It aims to recruit at least 2,000 GPs from overseas over the next three years.</p><p> </p><p>To improve retention, NHS England has launched the GP Career Plus Scheme, to test a range of ways to offer flexibility and support to experienced GPs at risk of leaving general practice. This is in addition to the new GP Retention Scheme which offers funding to support doctors who can only work a limited number of sessions in general practice.</p><p> </p><p>Finally, in October 2016, NHS England announced a package of improvements to the GP Induction and Refresher Scheme to make it easier and quicker for qualified doctors to return to general practice.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-11T14:32:59.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757724/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757724/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757724/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","General Practitioners: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress he has made to meet the target of 5,000 additional GPs by 2020.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","8730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757725","Department of Health","false","2017-09-13","<p>Information, including the date at which an opportunity is advertised (published date) and the date at which the contract is awarded (Awarded date) can be found via ContractsFinder, the Government’s procurement gateway tool. This is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search" target="_blank">https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search</a></p><p> </p><p>Users should enter Department of Health into the Key Words search box, then choose ‘Awarded’ as far as ‘Notice status’, then finally choose the CSV download option.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-09-13T10:07:10.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757725/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757725/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757725/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Department of Health: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many procurements undertaken by his Department have taken more than (a) three months, (b) six months, (c) one year and (d) two years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8758"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757726","Home Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The decision to procure and deploy BWV cameras is a matter for Police and Crime Commissioners and chief officers.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-09-12T16:50:20.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757726/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757726/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757726/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Police: Cameras","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the use of body-worn cameras to capture evidence for use in law courts.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","8788"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757727","Home Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>The information requested is not currently held centrally.</p><p>However, Home Office are committed to the HMT Transparency Agenda and EU Competition regulations and therefore all contract requirements and awards that exceed the EU procurement directives' financial thresholds are advertised in the <a href="http://ted.publications.eu.int/official/" target="_blank">Supplement to the Official Journal of the European Union (OJEU)</a> via contract notices. Furthermore, all requirements and contract awards over £10,000 are published on <a href="https://online.contractsfinder.businesslink.gov.uk/" target="_blank">Contracts Finder</a> at this link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/contracts-finder" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/contracts-finder</a> .</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-09-13T15:51:28.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757727/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757727/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757727/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Home Office: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many procurements undertaken by her Department have taken more than (a) three months, (b) six months, (c) one year and (d) two years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757728","Home Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Government takes detainee welfare very seriously. Immediate action has been taken in response to the allegations raised by BBC Panorama. Sussex police has begun an investigation to establish whether criminal offences have been committed.</p><p> </p><p>G4S has suspended ten officers and is carrying out full investigations. The Home Office has suspended a former G4S officer, now a Home Office employee, and is carrying out an investigation.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-09-11T15:38:21.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757728/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757728/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757728/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Brook House Immigration Removal Centre","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether proceedings are being (a) considered and (b) brought against any individual members of (i) her Department's and (ii) G4S staff as a result of investigations arising from BBC Panorama's investigation into Brook House.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","8709"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757729","Home Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>Information on the non-crime activities and the data it is based on is included in the existing Police Allocation Formula is published annually in the Police Grant Report for England and Wales, most recently in February 2017.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/588196/Police_Grant_report_2017-18_Accessible.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/588196/Police_Grant_report_2017-18_Accessible.pdf</a></p><p>Population data was annually updated until 2010/11 since when forces have had their allocations of core Central Government funding reduced by the same percentage.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","8692","2017-09-11T16:38:37.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757729/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757729/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757729/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Police: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what categories of activity are considered to be Non-Crime Activity under the Police Allocation Formula; from where the data relating to such activities is drawn; and to what time period that data relates.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","8701"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757730","Home Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>Statistics on the European Arrest Warrant (EAW) are published by the National Crime Agency, these figures include the number of EAWs issued or received by the United Kingdom, arrests made under an EAW and the number of surrenders made under an EAW either to or from the UK.</p><p>The figures, since 2010, are published at: -</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.nationalcrimeagency.gov.uk/publications/european-arrest-warrant-statistics" target="_blank">http://www.nationalcrimeagency.gov.uk/publications/european-arrest-warrant-statistics</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-09-13T15:56:26.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757730/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757730/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757730/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","European Arrest Warrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when the Government plans to publish the most up-to-date European Arrest Warrant statistics.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","8677"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757731","Home Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>The information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-09-13T16:09:31.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757731/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757731/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757731/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Home Office: Sub-letting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much her Department has received from sub-lets on its estate in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8740"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757732","Home Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Government’s Written Ministerial Statement of Wednesday 12 July 2017 conveyed the main findings of the review into the funding for Islamist extremist activity in the UK. The review has improved the Government’s understanding of the nature, scale and sources of funding for Islamist extremism in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>The review’s report is classified because of the volume of personal information it contains and for national security reasons. The Written Ministerial Statement is a comprehensive and representative reflection of the review’s findings. The Government has no plans to comment further on the review’s findings. The Government’s priority is making the best use of the tools available to disrupt extremist activity in the UK.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-09-11T16:10:44.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757732/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757732/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757732/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to her Written Statement of 12 July 2017, HCWS39, on extremism, if the Government will publish information on Saudi funding for extremism in the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","8687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757733","Home Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Schengen Information System makes information available to UK law enforcement on: persons wanted for arrest by another participating State; missing persons in need of protection or whose whereabouts need to be ascertained; persons being investigated for serious offences or who are thought to present a threat to the public, and objects linked to them; persons needed to assist with a judicial procedure, e.g. potential witnesses; and objects sought for seizure or use as evidence in criminal proceedings.</p><p> </p><p>The Prime Minister has made clear that one of the twelve objectives for the negotiations ahead will be to establish a new relationship with the European Union that includes practical arrangements on matters of security and law enforcement cooperation to tackle cross-border crime and to keep our people safe.</p><p> </p><p>We continue to work closely with EU partners and we are examining the options for future cooperation arrangements once the UK has left the EU, but it would be wrong to set out unilateral positions on specific measures that currently facilitate our practical cooperation in advance of negotiations.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","8668","2017-09-11T16:40:45.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757733/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757733/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757733/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Schengen Agreement: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether it is the Government's policy to retain UK membership of the Schengen Information System after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","8667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757734","Home Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Schengen Information System makes information available to UK law enforcement on: persons wanted for arrest by another participating State; missing persons in need of protection or whose whereabouts need to be ascertained; persons being investigated for serious offences or who are thought to present a threat to the public, and objects linked to them; persons needed to assist with a judicial procedure, e.g. potential witnesses; and objects sought for seizure or use as evidence in criminal proceedings.</p><p> </p><p>The Prime Minister has made clear that one of the twelve objectives for the negotiations ahead will be to establish a new relationship with the European Union that includes practical arrangements on matters of security and law enforcement cooperation to tackle cross-border crime and to keep our people safe.</p><p> </p><p>We continue to work closely with EU partners and we are examining the options for future cooperation arrangements once the UK has left the EU, but it would be wrong to set out unilateral positions on specific measures that currently facilitate our practical cooperation in advance of negotiations.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","8667","2017-09-11T16:40:46.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757734/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757734/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757734/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Schengen Agreement: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will list the types of information currently available to UK enforcement agencies as a result of membership of the Schengen Information System.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","8668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757735","Home Office","false","2018-04-11","<p>The Government has no intention of reviewing its policy on arms exports to Saudi Arabia and the findings of the review into funding of Islamist extremist activity in the UK do not support one.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-04-11T09:44:06.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757735/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757735/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757735/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to her Written Statement of 12 July 2017 HCWS39, on extremism, whether the Government plans to review its policy on arms exports to Saudi Arabia as a result of her Department's review.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","8688"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757736","Home Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>We monitor the time it takes to decide applications for asylum support closely and have brought down the processing times over the last year. If a destitute asylum seeker has an immediate need for support, for example because they are homeless, they can apply to be admitted to emergency accommodation. We aim to make decisions on these cases on the same day.</p><p>The Government has a longstanding policy of only granting asylum seekers permission to work in the UK if their asylum claim has been outstanding for at least 12 months through no fault of their own and only in jobs on the shortage occupation list. There are no plans to change this policy.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-09-11T13:16:46.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757736/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757736/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757736/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what consideration has been given to decreasing delays in processing asylum support applications; and whether the Government has considered allowing people seeking sanctuary in the UK the right to work.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","8672"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757737","Home Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>Information on the non-crime activities and the data it is based on is included in the existing Police Allocation Formula is published annually in the Police Grant Report for England and Wales, most recently in February 2017.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/588196/Police_Grant_report_2017-18_Accessible.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/588196/Police_Grant_report_2017-18_Accessible.pdf</a></p><p>Population data was annually updated until 2010/11 since when forces have had their allocations of core Central Government funding reduced by the same percentage.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","8701","2017-09-11T16:38:37.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757737/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757737/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757737/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Police: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effect of changes in population in different parts of the UK since the 2001 Census on the allocation of resources under the police allocation formula.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","8692"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757738","Home Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>There are three private companies, Post Office, Royal Mail and National Air Traffic Services who have access to the Police National Computer. The following amounts were accrued from such companies:</p><p> </p><p>2014/15: £1982.21</p><p>2015/16: £3557.53</p><p>2016/17: £7384.14</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-09-13T14:32:30.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757738/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757738/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757738/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Police National Computer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many private companies have access to the Police National Computer; and how much accrued to the public purse from charges on such companies for access to that computer in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","8690"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757739","Home Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Home Office publishes information on visa processing times and the number of cases ‘in progress’ online at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data</a> (listed by publication date under ‘UK Visas &amp; Immigration’).</p><p>UK Visas and Immigration operate flexible staffing resources and deploy staff in line with demands on the service. Data on staffing within UK Visas &amp; Immigration is published online at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data#staffing-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data#staffing-data</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-09-11T13:53:21.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757739/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757739/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757739/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people are currently awaiting decisions on visas to enter the UK; how many officials work on the decision-making process for those visas; and what the average waiting time for a decision is in such cases.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","8597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757740","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-12","<p>As the British Transport Police (BTP) receives its funding from individual train operators it is not possible to provide the information requested. However, BTP’s C division, which covers West Yorkshire, has a specific commitment in its policing plan to prevent anti-social behaviour.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-12T14:05:57.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757740/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757740/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757740/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-05","British Transport Police: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what level of funding the British Transport Police has received to tackle anti-social behaviour on (a) trains and (b) trains stations in (i) West Yorkshire and (ii) England.","false","Biography information for Thelma Walker","Colne Valley","Thelma Walker","8664"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757741","Home Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Home Office constantly reviews its capabilities in order to deliver the Government’s agenda. With negotiations now underway, we continue to assess how our priorities will impact on the workforce and capabilities required. Operational units across the Home Office actively monitor workflows to ensure sufficient resources are in place to meet demand and will continue to do so throughout negotiations and as the UK leaves the EU. Any resultant changes to resource requirements will be factored into strategic planning.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-09-11T13:57:57.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757741/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757741/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757741/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Home Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many new staff her Department plans to employ to manage immigration to the UK after the UK leaves the EU; and how many staff she plans to redeploy from within her Department to work on registration and visa systems after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","8600"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757742","Home Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>The length of detention figures for people in the detention estate are available from the Home Office website at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/638608/detention-apr-jun-2017-tables.ods" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/638608/detention-apr-jun-2017-tables.ods</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-09-13T15:54:04.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757742/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757742/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757742/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Brook House Immigration Removal Centre","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the average length of time is that detainees have remained at Brook House Immigration Removal Centre in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","8542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757743","Home Office","false","2017-09-18","<p>The UKVI MP Account Management teams have offered a reduced phone service from 11am – 4pm since the beginning of recess to enable them to respond to an unprecedented increase in written enquiries from Members of Parliament. Hon. Members continue to be able to contact their MP Account Managers direct to raise urgent enquiries outside of these operating times. Records show that the teams are handling similar call volumes in the reduced operating hours.</p><p> </p><p>Reducing the operational hours of the service helps ensure that the teams continue to deliver high levels of service both on the phones and in writing.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-09-18T13:21:40.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757743/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757743/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757743/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, for what reasons her Department has reduced the operational hours of the Immigration and Asylum Unit for hon. Members during the 2017 Summer Recess.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","8543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757744","Home Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans the Government has to tackle trends in the incidence of the drug known as Spice</p><p><br> Use of new psychoactive substances has fallen significantly since we introduced the Psychoactive Substances Act, hundreds of retailers have shut and the first offenders have been convicted. <br> <br> However, the Government recognises how dangerous synthetic cannabinoids, such as those found in spice, can be and the devastating impact that they can have on those taking them. That is why we acted to control these substances as class B drugs under the Misuse of Drugs Act and give the police the powers they need to take action, including making possession illegal and delivering longer sentences for dealers</p><p><br> Our new Drug Strategy, emphasised the importance of a joined up approach to tackling the harms caused by drugs to prevent substance misuse, restrict the supply of drugs and support people from drug dependency. We strongly support the multi-agency approach being taken in areas to respond to this issue to reduce burden on public services and to prevent harm to the individuals themselves.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-09-13T15:25:07.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757744/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757744/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757744/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Synthetic Cannabinoids: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans the Government has to tackle trends in the incidence of the drug known as Spice.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Reynolds","Stalybridge and Hyde","Jonathan Reynolds","8685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757745","Home Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>The information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-09-13T15:50:05.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757745/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757745/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757745/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Home Office: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much her Department has paid in letting fees for its estate in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757746","Home Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Home Office published on 24 August 2017 a second report on statistics being collected under the exit checks programme (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/second-report-on-statistics-being-collected-under-the-exit-checks-programme" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/second-report-on-statistics-being-collected-under-the-exit-checks-programme</a>). Chapter 1 sets out the operational uses of the exit checks system as well as improvements to immigration control and compliance since 2010.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","8891","2017-09-13T15:57:43.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757746/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757746/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757746/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Borders: Personal Records","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how data from exit checks conducted between April 2015 and April 2016 has been used by her Department.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Davey","Kingston and Surbiton","Sir Edward Davey","8855"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757747","Home Office","false","2017-09-18","<p>There has been no policy change with regards to EEA citizens living in the UK and the Home Office is absolutely clear that the rights of EEA citizens living in the UK remain unchanged. It is Home Office policy that any person who is not lawfully resident in the UK is liable for removal and may be notified accordingly by the Home Office. I regret that, in this instance, officials made an operational error and issued enforcement letters incorrectly.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Home Office acted swiftly to correct the error and I have personally written to all those affected to apologise for any stress or concern that this caused.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","8890","2017-09-18T13:03:05.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757747/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757747/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757747/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Deportation: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, for what reasons her Department erroneously sent deportation letters to EU citizens lawfully living in the UK.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Davey","Kingston and Surbiton","Sir Edward Davey","8889"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757748","Home Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>There are a range of existing powers available for both the police and local authorities to tackle unauthorised encampments. The Criminal Justice and Public Order Act 1994 provides specific powers to the police to move travellers from unauthorised encampments if certain criteria are met.</p><p>The Home Office works closely with the police to ensure the powers they have are fit for purpose. However, the decision on when and whether to use police powers is an independent operational decision for the police.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-09-12T16:46:39.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757748/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757748/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757748/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Travellers: Caravan Sites","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of whether police forces in (a) England and (b) the West Midlands are effective in using the powers available to them to remove Travellers from unauthorised encampments.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","8902"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757749","Home Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>Citizens of Australia and New Zealand who regularly travel to the UK or hold a UK visa already have the option of becoming a member of the Registered Traveller Service, the benefits of which include use of the ePassport gates.</p><p> </p><p>A complete overview of the service and the eligibility requirements can be found at: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/registered-traveller" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/registered-traveller</a>.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-09-13T15:59:26.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757749/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757749/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757749/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Immigration Controls: Australasia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans the Government has to make the e-passport gates at UK airports available to citizens of Australia and New Zealand.","false","Biography information for John Spellar","Warley","John Spellar","8860"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757750","Home Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Ipsos Mori survey for HMIC “Public views of policing in England and Wales 2016/17” published on 20 July 2017 shows that: people are most likely to call 999 for crimes/incidents against the person; there is a balance between 999 and 101 for property-related incidents; while for online incidents, anti-social behaviour and updates on previous incidents, 101 is the most likely choice. The survey can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.ipsos.com/sites/default/files/2017-07/public-views-of-policing-2017-hmic.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.ipsos.com/sites/default/files/2017-07/public-views-of-policing-2017-hmic.pdf</a></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-09-12T16:31:29.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757750/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757750/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757750/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","101 Calls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the efficacy of the 101 service for reporting low level crime.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","8982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757751","Home Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>The handling of 101 calls is an operational matter for the police. The Home Office does not request 101 data from forces.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","8963","2017-09-13T16:11:32.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757751/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757751/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757751/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","101 Calls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the average waiting time was by local authority area for calls to the 101 non-emergency crime reporting service in the most recent year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","8983"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757752","Home Office","false","2017-09-20","<p>The 2015 Spending Review protected overall police spending in real terms. Since 2015/16 police forces have received broadly flat cash budgets and we are increasing investment in transformation, improved communications and technology capabilities</p><p> </p><p>Decisions on the most effective use of the Metropolitan Police’s resources are for Chief Officers and the Mayor’s Office for Policing and Crime (MOPAC) who are held to account by the communities they serve.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-09-20T13:21:02.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757752/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757752/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757752/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Police: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to ensure that areas with historically low levels of crime continue to receive necessary levels of funding for local police.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","8981"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757753","Home Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>The handling of 101 calls is an operational matter for the police. The Home Office does not request 101 data from forces.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","8983","2017-09-13T16:11:32.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757753/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757753/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757753/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","101 Calls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that operators on the 101 non-emergency crime reporting service have sufficient knowledge of the local areas for which they are responsible.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","8963"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757754","Home Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>The A2 level English language requirement under the family Immigration Rules applies to applications for further temporary leave to remain as a partner or parent, after 30 months in the UK on a five-year route to settlement. We expect those coming to the UK on a family visa with only basic English to become more fluent over time, to support their integration. The requested breakdown of refusals would require a manual review of all relevant applications, which would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","8953","2017-09-13T15:58:38.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757754/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757754/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757754/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effect of the new A2 qualification requirement on non-UK residents seeking permanent leave to remain.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","8952"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757755","Home Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>The A2 level English language requirement under the family Immigration Rules applies to applications for further temporary leave to remain as a partner or parent, after 30 months in the UK on a five-year route to settlement. We expect those coming to the UK on a family visa with only basic English to become more fluent over time, to support their integration. The requested breakdown of refusals would require a manual review of all relevant applications, which would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","8952","2017-09-13T15:58:38.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757755/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757755/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757755/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many applications for permanent leave to remain have been refused as a result of not meeting the new A2 qualification, for each parliamentary constituency.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","8953"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757756","Home Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The handling of 101 calls is an operational matter for the police. The Home Office does not request 101 data from forces.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-09-12T16:35:02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757756/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757756/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757756/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","101 Calls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many calls to the 101 non-emergency crime reporting service were terminated by the caller while waiting for an operator in each local authority area in the most recent year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","8964"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757757","Home Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The decision to procure and deploy BWV cameras is a matter for Police and Crime Commissioners and chief officers. The Home Office is aware that most forces in England and Wales use BWV to some extent. Each force will have its own implementation plan and schedule for the rollout of cameras, but this information is not held centrally.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-09-12T16:52:08.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757757/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757757/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757757/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Police: Cameras","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will bring forward legislative proposals to make it a requirement for all on-duty uniformed and armed police to wear body cameras.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","8897"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757758","Home Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>Officials have met with the UK Cleaning Products Industry Association and are meeting the Chemical Business Association, to discuss how they can support action to prevent the use of acid and other corrosives as a weapon.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-09-13T15:49:49.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757758/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757758/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757758/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Crimes of Violence: Acids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent discussions she has had with the pharmaceutical industry on preventing household products being used in acid attacks.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","8936"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757759","Home Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Government has noted the report by the Human Trafficking Foundation into the independent inquiry into the situation of separated and unaccompanied minors in parts of Europe and is considering its recommendations. We are already working on a number of the areas addressed in the report.</p><p> </p><p>The UK is working very closely with France and other EU Member States in respect of unaccompanied asylum-seeking children. This includes ensuring the timely and efficient operation of the Dublin Regulation, to allow children with qualifying family in the UK to be transferred here for consideration of their asylum claim, where it is in the child’s best interests. We also remain fully committed to implementing section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016, and are working with Member State authorities and other partners to identify and transfer children to the UK quickly and safely. However, the primary responsibility for unaccompanied children lies with the authorities in the country in which children are present. The UK government does not have the authority to operate unauthorised on the territory of another sovereign state.</p><p>The Department for Education and Home Office continue to work together with local authorities and NGOs to ensure that vulnerable children are safe, and their welfare promoted once they arrive in the UK. A joint safeguarding strategy for unaccompanied asylum-seeking and refugee children is due to be published in the Autumn.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-09-11T13:54:26.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757759/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757759/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757759/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if her Department will consider the recommendations of the report by Christine Beddoe on separated and unaccompanied minors in Europe.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","8918"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757760","Home Office","false","2017-09-18","<p>There has been no policy change with regards to EEA citizens living in the UK and the Home Office is absolutely clear that the rights of EEA citizens living in the UK remain unchanged. It is Home Office policy that any person who is not lawfully resident in the UK is liable for removal and may be notified accordingly by the Home Office. I regret that, in this instance, officials made an operational error and issued enforcement letters incorrectly.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Home Office acted swiftly to correct the error and I have personally written to all those affected to apologise for any stress or concern that this caused.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","8889","2017-09-18T13:03:05.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757760/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757760/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757760/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Deportation: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what level of seniority the Official holds who was responsible for signing-off deportation letters which were erroneously sent by her Department to EU citizens lawfully living in the UK.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Davey","Kingston and Surbiton","Sir Edward Davey","8890"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757761","Home Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>The staffing of emergency service call centres is an operational matter for the police. Over thirty police forces across the country now operate some form of street triage scheme. Some of these consist of mental health professionals embedded in call centres, while others adopt a model of joint working between police officers and mental health professionals on the front line.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-09-13T15:53:21.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757761/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757761/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757761/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Emergency Services: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to ensure a trained mental health specialist is on duty in all emergency service call centres to assist with identifying callers who may require mental health support.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","8892"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757762","Home Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Home Office published on 24 August 2017 a second report on statistics being collected under the exit checks programme (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/second-report-on-statistics-being-collected-under-the-exit-checks-programme" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/second-report-on-statistics-being-collected-under-the-exit-checks-programme</a>). Chapter 1 sets out the operational uses of the exit checks system as well as improvements to immigration control and compliance since 2010.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","8855","2017-09-13T15:57:43.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757762/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757762/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757762/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Borders: Personal Records","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what analysis her Department has undertaken of the exit check data collated by her Department between April 2015 and April 2016.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Davey","Kingston and Surbiton","Sir Edward Davey","8891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757763","Home Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Police and Criminal Evidence Act 1983 (PACE) sets out the statutory framework governing the duties of the police in respect of custodial care and the rights and entitlements of a detainee in police custody, including healthcare. Ensuring these requirements are met is an operational matter for the police.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, Liaison and Diversion schemes, which provide a referral service into assessment and support services for those in custody with mental health or substance misuse issues currently cover 68 per cent of the population of England. Roll out is continuing and coverage is expected to extend to 82 per cent of the country by April 2018.</p><p> </p><p>Her Majesty’s Inspectorate of Constabulary has a rolling programme of police force inspections, which includes the treatment of detainees and conditions in police custody. Reports are published on the Justice Inspectorates website.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-09-11T16:42:03.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757763/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757763/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757763/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Police Custody: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the adequacy of mental health support available to people detained in police custody.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","8974"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757764","Home Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>The review is being carefully considered and it will be published in due course.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-09-11T16:35:24.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757764/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757764/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757764/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Deaths and Serious Incidents in Police Custody Independent Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when the Independent Review of Deaths and Serious Incidents in Police Custody announced on 23 July 2015 will be published.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","8975"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757765","Home Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>The provision of police custody healthcare services is the responsibility of individual Police and Crime Commissioners. Information on the companies that provide these services is an operational policing matter and not held centrally by the Home Office.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-09-11T16:44:31.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757765/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757765/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757765/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-05","Police Custody: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many police forces use private companies to provide healthcare to people held in police custody.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","8976"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757766","Department for International Development","false","2017-09-12","<p>DFID delivers bilateral forest programmes focused on tackling illegal logging and related corruption, encouraging sustainable trade based on legal and sustainable supplies of timber and agricultural commodities, and improving the livelihoods of indigenous people and local communities which depend on forests for their livelihoods. DFID also funds multilateral programmes which promote forest conservation and management, including through the Green Climate Fund, Global Environment Facility and the Forest Investment Programme.</p><p>DFID funding for forest conservation and management was £38m in FY12-13, £44m in FY13-14, £170m in FY14-15, £75m in FY15-16 and £69m in FY16-17, including bilateral programmes and multilateral contributions.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-09-12T17:00:42.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757766/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757766/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757766/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-05","Forests: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much her Department has spent on forest conservation projects overseas in the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","8960"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757767","Department for International Development","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Department supports marine conservation activities overseas through our funding to the UN Food and Agriculture Organisation (FAO) and the Global Environment Facility (GEF). For example FAO hosts the International Plan of Action to Prevent, Deter, and Eliminate Illegal, Unreported and Unregulated Fishing. The GEF has funded marine protected areas across the world that are more than twice the size of Alaska.</p><p>The UK’s core support to FAO in the past five years was a total of £92 million, comprising £42 million in 2012/13, £32 million in 2014/15 and £18 million in 2016/17. DFID’s contribution to the Global Environment Facility in the past five years was £262.5 million, comprising £52.5 million per year for each of the financial years from 2012 to 2016 inclusive. Neither FAO nor the GEF publish a breakdown of spending specifically on marine conservation.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-09-12T17:01:30.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757767/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757767/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757767/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-05","Marine Environment: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much her Department has spent on marine conservation projects overseas in the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","8961"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757768","Department for International Development","false","2017-09-12","<p>DFID has not paid any letting fees.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-09-12T14:43:16.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757768/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757768/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757768/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-05","Department for International Development: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much her Department has paid in letting fees for its estate in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757769","Department for International Development","false","2017-09-12","<p>No companies, charities or social enterprises in the Stirling constituency have a direct contract with DFID to supply goods or services.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-09-12T14:43:55.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757769/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757769/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757769/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-05","Department for International Development: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, which companies, charities and social enterprises in Stirling constituency supply goods and services to her Department.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","8806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757770","Department for International Development","false","2017-09-12","<p>All UK aid in Rwanda is earmarked for specific programmes only, such as education and agriculture, and is subject to robust monitoring to ensure results and value for money for the UK taxpayer. Our aid helps to lift a quarter of a million Rwandans out of poverty every year.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-09-12T17:02:02.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757770/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757770/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757770/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-05","Rwanda: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to monitor the use of UK Foreign Aid in Rwanda.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","8624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757771","Department for International Development","false","2017-09-13","<p>HMG was very concerned at some of the findings of the IMPACT-SE report and met with IMPACT-SE to discuss them. Our assessment is that IMPACT-SE report was not objective in its findings. We work closely with the Palestinian Authority Ministry of Education on quality of education issues.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-13T16:04:25.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757771/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757771/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757771/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-05","Palestinians: Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Memorandum of Understanding between the Palestinian Authority and her Department, signed in 2014, what assessment her Department has made to the findings and recommendations of the IMPACT-se report on the Palestinian Elementary School Curriculum 2016-17, published in April 2017.","true","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","8642"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757772","Department for International Development","false","2017-09-11","<p>Our partnership with the Palestinian Authority includes a commitment from the Palestinian leadership to adhere to the principle of non-violence and to tackle language that could incite violence or hatred. While we have not raised this specific issue with the Palestinian Authority, HMG regularly lobby the Palestinian leadership to tackle language that could incite violence or hatred, including anti-Semitic language. I raised this at the highest levels during my recent visit.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-11T16:55:43.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757772/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757772/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757772/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-05","Latifa Abu Hmeid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Memorandum of Understanding between her Department and the Palestinian Authority, signed in 2014, what discussions her Department has had with the Palestinian Authority on the recent decision of President Abbas to meet, and the Authority to honour, Latifa Abu Hmeid.","true","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","8641"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757773","Department for International Development","false","2017-09-11","<p>Our partnership with the Palestinian Authority includes a commitment from the Palestinian leadership to adhere to the principle of non-violence and to tackle language that could incite violence or hatred, including anti-Semitic language. While we have not raised this specific issue with the Palestinian Authority, HMG regularly lobby the Palestinian leadership to tackle language that could incite violence or hatred, including anti-Semitic language. I raised this at the highest levels during my recent visit.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-11T16:55:17.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757773/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757773/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757773/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-05","Palestinians: Higher Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Memorandum of Understanding between her Department and the Palestinian Authority, signed in 2014, what discussions her Department has had with the Palestinian Authority regarding President Abbas' decision to appoint Imad Hamato to the post of dean of the Al-Azhar Institutes in Gaza.","true","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","8640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757774","Department for International Development","false","2017-09-12","<p>DFID does not receive any income from sub-lets.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-09-12T14:40:58.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757774/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757774/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757774/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-05","Department for International Development: Sub-letting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much her Department has received from sub-lets on its estate in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8741"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757775","Department for International Development","false","2017-09-11","<p>DFID’s work has been pivotal in supporting the governments of Bangladesh and Nepal to respond quickly and effectively to help people who have been affected. In each affected country:</p><p> </p><ul><li><strong>Bangladesh</strong>: DFID made the first international contribution of £660,000 – the largest contributor after Government of Bangladesh itself -to those affected by the floods, via a consortium of NGOs. This will help over 60,000 people with food, shelter, and water and sanitation.</li><li><strong>Nepal:</strong> DFID has also allocated £400,000 to the Nepal Red Cross Society for water, sanitation, livelihood recovery and health. DFID has also responded through the START Fund global consortia of NGOs, which responds to small and medium emergencies. The multi-donor global START Fund has allocated £325,000.</li><li><strong>India:</strong> The START Fund has allocated £400,000 for India. The Indian Government has not requested assistance.</li><li><strong>Pakistan</strong>: DFID has funded a rapid assessment around Karachi and Sindh to identify potential needs.</li></ul><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-11T16:56:22.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757775/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757775/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757775/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-05","South Asia: Floods","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what humanitarian support the Government has provided (a) to each country and (b) by each delivery agency in response to the recent flooding in South Asia.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","8705"
